Defs: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a microvillus, a thin cylindrical membrane-covered projection on the surface of a cell.

label: cranial skeletal system
Defs: Skeletal subdivision of the head including skull (cranium plus mandible), pharyngeal and/or hyoid apparatus.

label: positive regulation of lymphocyte activation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of lymphocyte activation.

label: aliform
Defs: Shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being shaped like a wing.

label: regulation of stem cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of stem cell proliferation. A stem cell is a cell that retains the ability to divide and proliferate throughout life to provide progenitor cells that can differentiate into specialized cells.

label: distal to
Defs: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being located further from a more centrally located entity.

label: dorsum of tongue
Defs: The superior surface of the tongue divided by the sulcus terminalis into an anterior two-thirds, the presulcal part (pars presulcalis). and a posterior one-third, the postsulcal part (pars postsulcalis).

label: Schwann cell development
Defs: The process aimed at the progression of a Schwann cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell. Schwann cells are found in the peripheral nervous system, where they insulate neurons and axons, and regulate the environment in which neurons function.

label: interleukin-7 receptor subunit alpha (mouse)
Defs: An interleukin-7 receptor subunit alpha that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: female fertile
Defs: A female fertility quality inhering in a female by virtue of the bearer\'s disposition to initiate, sustain, or support reproduction.

label: desaturated violet
Defs: A color consisting of violet hue and low saturation.

label: amide biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of an amide, any derivative of an oxoacid in which an acidic hydroxy group has been replaced by an amino or substituted amino group.

label: author summary section
Defs: A part of a document, distinct from the abstract, that describes the significance and broader context of the document content. The author summary is often written in a non-technical manner and is aimed at both scientists and non-scientist readers.

label: flagellum
Defs: The endophallite that is elongated.

label: random pattern
Defs: characterised by an unidentifiable pattern.

label: abdominal sternite IX
Defs: The abdominal sternite of the postabdomen that is attached to the posterior margin of the abdominal sternite VIII by the abdominal sternite VIII-abdominal sternite IX conjunctiva and to the anterior margin of the abdominal sternite X by the abdominal sternite IX-abdominal sternite X conjunctiva.

label: tongue muscle
Defs: The muscular portion of the tongue.

label: cardiac septum morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structure of a cardiac septum is generated and organized. A cardiac septum is a partition that separates parts of the heart.

label: alaforamen
Defs: The arthropod foramen that is part of the foramen occipitale and is located above the tentorial bridge.

label: focus
Defs: An optical quality where light rays originating from a point on the object converge.

label: negative regulation of organic acid transport
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of organic acids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: future brain
Defs: The embryonic precursor of the brain.

label: positive regulation of neutrophil chemotaxis
Defs: Any process that increases the frequency, rate, or extent of neutrophil chemotaxis. Neutrophil chemotaxis is the directed movement of a neutrophil cell, the most numerous polymorphonuclear leukocyte found in the blood, in response to an external stimulus, usually an infection or wounding.

label: positive regulation of lysosome organization
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of lysosome organization.

label: ventral-longitudinal muscle
Defs: The insect thoracic muscle that is not fan-shaped and runs along the ventral region, parallel to the anterior-posterior axis.

label: spinal nerve
Defs: The any of the paired peripheral nerves formed by the union of the dorsal and ventral spinal roots from each spinal cord segment[MP,modified].

label: cell-cell fusion
Defs: A cellular process in which two or more cells combine together, their plasma membrane fusing, producing a single cell. In some cases, nuclei fuse, producing a polyploid cell, while in other cases, nuclei remain separate, producing a syncytium.

label: organic cyclic compound catabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of organic cyclic compound.

label: concave 3-D shape
Defs: A complete three dimensional shape in which there is a line connecting pair of points on the object that lies outside the object. Or: a shape with cavities. Contrast: concave.

label: regulation of translation by machinery localization
Defs: Any process in which proteins and protein complexes involved in translation are transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.

label: cuticular groove
Defs: The cuticular depression that does not correspond to an epithelial fold.

label: hormone transport
Defs: The directed movement of hormones into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: positive regulation of smooth muscle contraction
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle contraction.

label: normal adhesivity
Defs: A adhesivity which is relatively normal or average.

label: gonadal mesoderm development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the gonadal mesoderm over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The gonadal mesoderm is the middle layer of the three primary germ layers of the embryo which will go on to form the gonads of the organism.

label: dermal skeleton
Defs: Skeletal subdivision that undergoes direct development and includes elements that either develop in association with the basement membrane of the ectoderm or are homologous with such elements; includes dermatocranium, components of the appendicular skeleton, teeth and tooth-like elements of the oropharynx, and integumentary elements.

label: straight angle to
Defs: An angle which is 180 degrees to another entity.

label: vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 binding
Defs: Binding to a vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2.

label: saturated magenta
Defs: A color consisting of magenta color and high saturation.

label: antennal foramen
Defs: The arthropod foramen of the head capsule that contains the antennifer and surrounds the scapus via the antenniferal-scapal conjunctiva.

label: negative regulation of chromosome condensation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of chromosome condensation.

label: epithelial to mesenchymal transition
Defs: A transition where an epithelial cell loses apical/basolateral polarity, severs intercellular adhesive junctions, degrades basement membrane components and becomes a migratory mesenchymal cell.

label: intrinsic component of synaptic membrane
Defs: The component of the synaptic membrane consisting of the gene products and protein complexes having either part of their peptide sequence embedded in the hydrophobic region of the membrane or some other covalently attached group such as a GPI anchor that is similarly embedded in the membrane.

label: mesothelium
Defs: Simple squamous epithelium of mesodermal origin which lines serous membranes. Examples: mesothelium of pleura, mesothelium of peritoneum[FMA]. Wikipedia: The mesothelium is a membrane that forms the lining of several body cavities: the pleura (thoracal cavity), peritoneum (abdominal cavity including the mesentery) and pericardium (heart sac). Mesothelial tissue also surrounds the male internal reproductive organs (the tunica vaginalis testis) and covers the internal reproductive organs of women (the tunica serosa uteri).

label: serous cell of epithelium of lobular bronchiole
Defs: A serous secreting cell that is part of the epithelium of bronchiole.

label: skeletal ligament
Defs: Dense regular connective tissue connecting two or more adjacent skeletal elements[VSAO,modified].

label: internal genitalia
Defs: The internal genitalia are the internal sex organs such as the uterine tube, the uterus and the vagina in female mammals, and the testis, seminal vesicle, ejaculatory duct and prostate in male mammals.

label: documenting
Defs: A planned process in which a document is created or added to by including the specified input in it.

label: homophilic
Defs: A cellular adhesivity quality inhering in a molecule in one cell by virtue of the bearer\'s attachment to an identical molecule in an adjacent cell.

label: petrosal placode
Defs: Epibranchial placode between geniculate and nodose. Associated with 2nd branchial cleft.

label: glucose
Defs: An aldohexose used as a source of energy and metabolic intermediate.

label: secretory granule membrane
Defs: The lipid bilayer surrounding a secretory granule.

label: regulation of neural crest cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of neural crest cell differentiation.

label: heart endothelium
Defs: An endothelium that is part of a heart [Automatically generated definition].

label: pleural wing process
Defs: The cuticular protrusion of the pleuron that is connected lateraly to the notum.

label: negative regulation of post-embryonic development
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of post-embryonic development. Post-embryonic development is defined as the process whose specific outcome is the progression of the organism over time, from the completion of embryonic development to the mature structure.

label: synapse
Defs: The junction between an axon of one neuron and a dendrite of another neuron, a muscle fiber or a glial cell. As the axon approaches the synapse it enlarges into a specialized structure, the presynaptic terminal bouton, which contains mitochondria and synaptic vesicles. At the tip of the terminal bouton is the presynaptic membrane; facing it, and separated from it by a minute cleft (the synaptic cleft) is a specialized area of membrane on the receiving cell, known as the postsynaptic membrane. In response to the arrival of nerve impulses, the presynaptic terminal bouton secretes molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane.

label: molecular function regulator activity
Defs: A molecular function regulator regulates the activity of its target via non-covalent binding that does not result in covalent modification to the target. Examples of molecular function regulators include regulatory subunits of multimeric enzymes and channels. Mechanisms of regulation include allosteric changes in the target and competitive inhibition.

label: compound eye photoreceptor cell
Defs: Any photoreceptor cell that is part of a compound eye.

label: superior side
Defs: The side that is higher relative to the substrate.

label: retinal melanocyte
Defs: A melanocyte of the retina. This cell type is distinct from pigmented retinal epithelium.

label: negative regulation of aorta morphogenesis
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of aorta morphogenesis.

label: phosphate ion homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of phosphate ions within an organism or cell.

label: sodium(1+)
Defs: A monoatomic monocation obtained from sodium.

label: organic substance biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of an organic substance, any molecular entity containing carbon.

label: hindgut development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the hindgut over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The hindgut is part of the alimentary canal that lies posterior to the midgut.

label: lateral and rotional curvature
Defs: A curvature quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being curved around an axis and towards the side.

label: acetylcholine receptor activator activity
Defs: Interacting (directly or indirectly) with acetylcholine receptors such that the proportion of receptors in the active form is increased.

label: realizable entity
Defs: A specifically dependent continuant  that inheres in continuant  entities and are not exhibited in full at every time in which it inheres in an entity or group of entities. The exhibition or actualization of a realizable entity is a particular manifestation, functioning or process that occurs under certain circumstances.

label: pronoto-occipital muscle
Defs: The dorsal longitudinal thoracic muscle that is attached to the pronotum and the postocciput.

label: oblate
Defs: A spheroid quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s exhibiting an equatorial diameter greater than its polar diameter.

label: posterodorsal to
Defs: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being located toward the rear and upper surface of an organism relative to another entity.

label: bronchial mucosa
Defs: A mucosa that is part of a bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

label: obsolete2_binary executable
Defs: Binary executable is a digital entity consisting of the binary representation of machine instructions of a specific processor or they may be binary pseudocode for a virtual machine. A non-source executable file is also called an object program. It is assumed that the binary executable file contains properly-formatted computer instructions.  (derived from Wikipedia, Nov 1, 2007)

label: lysosomal transport
Defs: The directed movement of substances into, out of or within a lysosome.

label: female organism
Defs: Gonochoristic organism that can produce female gametes.

label: collagen network
Defs: A supramolecular complex that consists of collagen triple helices associated to form a network.

label: left hepatic duct
Defs: The duct that drains bile from the left half of the liver and joins the right hepatic duct to form the common hepatic duct.

label: anteromedially rotated
Defs: A rotation quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of being rotated towards the front and the middle of an organism.

label: decreased variability of size
Defs: A variability of size which is relatively low.

label: regulation of keratinocyte migration
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of keratinocyte migration.

label: regulation of myeloid dendritic cell cytokine production
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of myeloid dendritic cell cytokine production.

label: positive regulation of protein secretion
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the controlled release of a protein from a cell.

label: intramembranous bone
Defs: Bone tissue forms directly within mesenchyme, and does not replace other tissues[TAO]. Intramembranous ossification is the formation of bone in which osteoblasts secrete a collagen-proteoglycan matrix that binds calcium salts and becomes calcified[GO]. Intramembranous ossification is the way flat bones and the shell of a turtle are formed[GO]. Unlike endochondral ossification, cartilage is not present during intramembranous ossification[WP].

label: protein catabolic process, modulating synaptic transmission
Defs: Any protein degradation process, occurring at a presynapse, that regulates synaptic transmission.

label: secretion of endocrine pancreas
Defs: A secretion that is part of a endocrine pancreas [Automatically generated definition].

label: cellular anatomical entity
Defs: A part of a cellular organism that is either an immaterial entity or a material entity with granularity above the level of a protein complex but below that of an anatomical system. Or, a substance produced by a cellular organism with granularity above the level of a protein complex.

label: lethargic
Defs: A behavioral quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being deficient in alertness or activity.

label: cell fate commitment involved in pattern specification
Defs: The commitment of cells to specific cell fates and their capacity to differentiate into particular kinds of cells within a field of cells that will exhibit a certain pattern of differentiation. Positional information is established through protein signals that emanate from a localized source within a developmental field resulting in specification of a cell type. Those signals are then interpreted in a cell-autonomous manner resulting in the determination of the cell type.

label: zymogen granule membrane
Defs: The lipid bilayer surrounding a zymogen granule.

label: wholly anterioralized
Defs: An anterioralized quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s gross morphology containing only what are normally anterior structures.

label: protuberance
Defs: A roughly circular bulge in a surface.

label: hyoid neural crest
Defs: Cranial neural crest that migrates into the hyoid arch.

label: gustatory epithelium
Defs: A sensory epithelium that is part of a gustatory system.

label: endothelial cell of periportal hepatic sinusoid
Defs: An endothelial cell found in the periportal region hepatic sinusoid, near the portal triad. The fenestrae of these cells are larger but fewer in number compared with those of endothelial cells near the centrilobular region of the hepatic sinusoid.

label: right lung associated mesenchyme
Defs: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing right lung.

label: regulation of cardiac muscle fiber development
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle fiber development.

label: lateral mesoderm formation
Defs: The process that gives rise to the lateral mesoderm. This process pertains to the initial formation of the structure from unspecified parts.

label: thalamic complex
Defs: A nuclear complex which in mammals consists of four parts, the hypothalamus, epithalamus, ventral thalamus, and dorsal thalamus[WP,modified].

label: mesonotum
Defs: The notum or sclerite on the dorsal region of the mesothorax that is posterior to the pronotum, connected via the mesonoto-mesopleural conjuntiva to the dorsal margin of the mesopleuron, that is not adjacent to the mesocoxa, but attached to it by the mesocoxal muscle.

label: regulation of somatic stem cell division
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of somatic stem cell division.

label: semi-lethal (sensu genetics)
Defs: A viability quality inhering in a bearer or a population by virtue of some of it\'s members\' inability to survive to reproduce.

label: radiopaque
Defs: A radiopacity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s prevention of the passage of electromagnetic radiation.

label: negative regulation of leukocyte mediated immunity
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of leukocyte mediated immunity.

label: regulation of smooth muscle contraction
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle contraction.

label: cytoplasmic microtubule depolymerization
Defs: The removal of tubulin heterodimers from one or both ends of a cytoplasmic microtubule.

label: regulation of translational initiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of translational initiation.

label: negative regulation of macrophage apoptotic process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of macrophage apoptotic process.

label: rectosigmoid junction
Defs: An anatomical junction that is between the sigmoid colon and rectum.

label: positive regulation of phosphorylation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of addition of phosphate groups to a molecule.

label: temperature
Defs: A physical quality of the thermal energy of a system.

label: mesothelial cell of colon
Defs: A mesothelial cell that is part of the colon.

label: retrograde trans-synaptic signaling by lipid
Defs: Cell-cell signaling from postsynapse to presynapse, across the synaptic cleft, mediated by a lipid ligand.

label: positive regulation of lymphocyte migration
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of lymphocyte migration.

label: cavity of right atrium
Defs: Luminal space of the right atrium of the heart.

label: muscle tissue development
Defs: The progression of muscle tissue over time, from its initial formation to its mature state. Muscle tissue is a contractile tissue made up of actin and myosin fibers.

label: stipito-lacinial muscle
Defs: The insect cranio-maxillar muscle that is attached to the stipes and the lacinia.

label: positive regulation of adaptive immune response
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of an adaptive immune response.

label: developing neuroepithelium
Defs: An embryonic or larval epithelium that is committed to form part of the nervous system.

label: regulation of neurotransmitter transport
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a neurotransmitter into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: chordamesoderm
Defs: The central region of trunk mesoderm. This tissue forms the notochord.

label: chamber of eyeball
Defs: A segment of the eyeball that is filled with refractive media.

label: negative regulation of cardiac ventricle development
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac ventricle development.

label: iridescent
Defs: A quality of certain surfaces which appear to change colour as the angle of view changes.

label: mouth-foregut junction
Defs: An anatomical junctions that overlaps the mouth and foregut.

label: cytokine receptor binding
Defs: Binding to a cytokine receptor.

label: measurement unit label
Defs: A measurement unit label is as a label that is part of a scalar measurement datum and denotes a unit of measure.

label: detection of chemical stimulus involved in sensory perception
Defs: The series of events in which a chemical stimulus is received and converted into a molecular signal as part of sensory perception.

label: aerobic (for occurrence)
Defs: A sensitivity of a process inhering in a biological process by virtue of the process unfolding in a location with oxygen.

label: neural rod
Defs: A solid rod of neurectoderm derived from the neural keel. The neural rod is roughly circular in cross section. Neural rod formation occurs during primary neurulation in teleosts[GO]. An intermediate stage in the development of the central nervous system present during the segmentation period; the neural rod is roughly cylindrical in shape, forms from the neural keel, and is not yet hollowed out into the neural tube[ZFIN].

label: pupal
Defs: A maturity quality inhering in a insect by virtue of the bearer\'s being in the chrysalis (cocoon) or post larval stage.

label: food component
Defs: A physiological role played by any substance that is distributed in foodstuffs. It includes materials derived from plants or animals, such as vitamins or minerals, as well as environmental contaminants.

label: neural crest-derived structure
Defs: An anatomical structure that develops from the neural crest.

label: endothelial transcription factor GATA-2
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human GATA2 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: unornamented
Defs: A surface feature shape in which the bearer\'s surface is lacking ridges, pits, rugosity or other surface structures.

label: intracellular lipid transport
Defs: The directed movement of lipids within cells.

label: negative regulation of somatostatin secretion
Defs: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, extent of the regulated release of somatostatin from secretory granules in the D cells of the pancreas.

label: regulation of myeloid cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of myeloid cell differentiation.

label: diencephalon neural crest
Defs: A neural crest that has_potential_to_developmentally_contribute_to a diencephalon.

label: regulation of dendritic cell antigen processing and presentation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of dendritic cell antigen processing and presentation.

label: regulation of smooth muscle hypertrophy
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle hypertrophy.

label: taenidium
Defs: The coiled ridge in the wall of the trachea.

label: dorso-lateral region
Defs: Anatomical region that overlaps the dorsal and lateral regions of a body or body part.

label: mandibular process mesenchyme
Defs: Mesenchyme that is part of a mandibular prominence.

label: somatostatin signaling pathway
Defs: A G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway initiated by somatostatin binding to a somatostatin receptor (SSTR), and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

label: isosceles triangular
Defs: A triangular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having two sides have the same length.

label: excitatory synapse
Defs: A synapse in which an action potential in the presynaptic cell increases the probability of an action potential occurring in the postsynaptic cell.

label: vasculature of central nervous system plus retina
anorectum
Defs: A subdivision of the digestive tract in humans that includes the rectum, the anal canal and the anus.

label: retuse
Defs: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s terminating in a round end, the centre of which is depressed.

label: transferase complex, transferring phosphorus-containing groups
Defs: A transferase complex capable of catalysis of the transfer of a phosphorus-containing group from one compound (donor) to another (acceptor).

label: negative regulation of catecholamine metabolic process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving catecholamine.

label: evaginated
Defs: A part or structure that is produced by evagination.

label: radioactive
Defs: A radiation quality inhering in bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s exhibiting or being caused by radioactivity.

label: coronal suture
Defs: The longitudinal cuticular suture that is on the vertex and is connected to the frontal suture.

label: Slamf1-positive multipotent progenitor cell
Defs: A hematopoietic progenitor that has some limited self-renewal capability. Cells are lin-negative, Kit-positive, CD34-positive, and Slamf1-positive.

label: dendritic transport of ribonucleoprotein complex
Defs: The directed movement of a ribonucleoprotein complex along microtubules in nerve cell dendrites.

label: glycogen biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycogen, a polydisperse, highly branched glucan composed of chains of D-glucose residues.

label: pulmonary artery morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the pulmonary artery are generated and organized. The pulmonary artery is the artery that carries blood from the heart to the lungs.

label: neurotransmitter metabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving neurotransmitters, any of a group of substances that are released on excitation from the axon terminal of a presynaptic neuron of the central or peripheral nervous system and travel across the synaptic cleft to either excite or inhibit the target cell.

label: glandular cell of the large intestine
Defs: A glandular epithelial cell of the large intestine.

label: cell-cell junction assembly
Defs: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a junction between cells.

label: interatrial septum
Defs: A cardiac septum that divides the left and right atria of the heart.

label: outflow part of right atrium
Defs: Outflow part of atrium which consists of wall and cavity of the outflow part of right atrium and the tricuspid valve.[FMA].

label: reproductive structure
Defs: Any anatomical structure that is part of the reproductive system.

label: pelvic appendage
Defs: Paired appendage that consists of the posterior appendicular skeleton and associated soft and hard tissues, but excludes the pelvic girdle and its associated soft and hard tissues.

label: epithelium of midgut
Defs: An epithelium that is part of a midgut.

label: paired limb/fin field
Defs: A ring of cells capable of forming a limb or paired fin[Gilbert,modified].

label: uniporous sensillum
Defs: The seta that has one opening distally.

label: response to yeast
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a yeast species.

label: hypopharyngeomandibular muscle
Defs: The cranio-mandibular muscle that is attached to the suspensorium and the insect mandible.

label: smooth muscle myoblast
Defs: A precursor cell destined to differentiate into smooth muscle myocytes.

label: reproductive structure development
Defs: The reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of somatic structures that will be used in the process of creating new individuals from one or more parents, from their formation to the mature structures.

label: serous membrane
Defs: Multi-tissue structure that is comprised of a secretory epithelial layer (mesothelium) and a connective tissue layer.

label: obsolete germ line dependent fertility value
positive regulation of glycogen biosynthetic process
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycogen.

label: nuclear membrane organization
Defs: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the nuclear inner or outer membrane.

label: external to
Defs: Positional quality in which an entity is located outside of another entity.

label: positive regulation of cell population proliferation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of cell proliferation.

label: pro-T cell
Defs: A lymphoid progenitor cell of the T cell lineage, with some lineage specific marker expression, but not yet fully committed to the T cell lineage.

label: muscle layer of rectum
Defs: A muscle layer that is part of the rectum.

label: sloped
Defs: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having an oblique or slanted direction.

label: decreased fatigability
Defs: A fatigability which is relatively low.

label: myelinated nerve fiber
Defs: Axons of neurons encased in a lipoproteinaceous material called myelin. (MeSH).

label: transmembrane receptor protein tyrosine kinase activity
Defs: Combining with a signal and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction: ATP + a protein-L-tyrosine = ADP + a protein-L-tyrosine phosphate.

label: esophageal taste bud
Defs: A taste bud that is located in the esophagus.

label: ligneous
Defs: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer resembling wood.

label: cellular biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of substances, carried out by individual cells.

label: positive regulation of angiogenesis
Defs: Any process that activates or increases angiogenesis.

label: regulation of aortic smooth muscle cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of aortic smooth muscle cell differentiation.

label: myoblast migration
Defs: The orderly movement of a myoblast from one site to another, often during the development of a multicellular organism. A myoblast is a cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

label: cavity of right ventricle
Defs: Luminal space of the right ventricle of the heart.

label: circulatory organ
Defs: A hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, contributes to the circulation of lymph, blood or analogs. Examples: a chambered vertebrate heart; the tubular peristaltic heart of ascidians; the dorsal vessel of an insect; the lymoh heart of a reptile.

label: negative regulation of leukocyte migration
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of leukocyte migration.

label: future cardiac atrium
Defs: Multi-tissue structure that is part of the heart tube and will become the cardiac atrium.

label: transition element atom
Defs: An element whose atom has an incomplete d sub-shell, or which can give rise to cations with an incomplete d sub-shell.

label: positive regulation of protein localization to nucleolus
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to nucleolus.

label: pronoto-mesopectal conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva that is attached to the pronotum and the mesopectus.

label: peptide zwitterion
Defs: Zwitterionic form of any peptide where, in general, the amino terminus is positively charged and the carboxy terminus is negatively charged.

label: partially paralysed
Defs: A functionality quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of being not completely paralysed.

label: negative regulation of photoreceptor cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of photoreceptor cell differentiation. An example of this process is found in Drosophila melanogaster.

label: oblique to
Defs: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having a slanting direction (neither perpendicular nor parallel) relative to another entity.

label: procumbent
Defs: Growing horizontal to the ground without setting roots.

label: mesotrochantin
Defs: The trochantin that is located on the ventro-lateral region of the mesothorax and is attached to a mesocoxa and surrounded by the basal mesocoxal conjunctiva.

label: pancreatic PP cell development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a pancreatic PP cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A pancreatic polypeptide-producing cell is a cell in the pancreas that produces pancreatic polypeptide.

label: L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion
Defs: Zwitterionic form of an L-alpha-amino acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.

label: ecto-epithelial cell
Defs: An epithelial cell derived from ectoderm.

label: pancreatic epithelial bud
Defs: The embryonic pancreas develops from two separate anlagen in the foregut epithelium, one dorsal and two ventral pancreatic buds[PMID].

label: branching involved in blood vessel morphogenesis
Defs: The process of coordinated growth and sprouting of blood vessels giving rise to the organized vascular system.

label: discriminate
Defs: A discrimination quality in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being capable of perceiving differences between two or more stimuli.

label: regulation of chromosome organization
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a process involved in the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a chromosome.

label: regulation of nuclear migration along microtubule
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of nuclear migration along microtubule.

label: organic substance transport
Defs: The directed movement of organic substances into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, or within a multicellular organism by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. An organic substance is a molecular entity that contains carbon.

label: skin of neck
Defs: A zone of skin that is part of a neck [Automatically generated definition].

label: synovial fluid
Defs: Joint fluid is a transudate of plasma that is actively secreted by synovial cells.

label: meningeal vein
Defs: One of the veins draining a meninix.

label: dense mesenchyme tissue
Defs: Mesenchyme with little extracellular matrix.

label: negative regulation of protein localization to lysosome
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to lysosome.

label: carcinoembryonic antigen-related cell adhesion molecule 8
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human CEACAM8 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: lactotransferrin (mouse)
Defs: A lactotransferrin that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: extracellular matrix organization
Defs: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of an extracellular matrix.

label: melanosome membrane
Defs: The lipid bilayer surrounding a melanosome.

label: positive regulation of striated muscle cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of striated muscle cell differentiation.

label: cardiac neuron
Defs: A neuron that has its soma in the heart.

label: refrigerant
Defs: A substance used in a thermodynamic heat pump cycle or refrigeration cycle that undergoes a phase change from a gas to a liquid and back. Refrigerants are used in air-conditioning systems and freezers or refrigerators and are assigned a "R" number (by ASHRAE - formerly the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air Conditioning Engineers), which is determined systematically according to their molecular structure.

label: coelemic cavity lumen
Defs: The cavity within the body of all animals higher than the coelenterates and certain primitive worms, formed by the splitting of the embryonic mesoderm into two layers. In mammals it forms the peritoneal, pleural, and pericardial cavities.

label: regulation of carbohydrate catabolic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of carbohydrates.

label: amino acid zwitterion
Defs: The zwitterionic form of an amino acid having a negatively charged carboxyl group and a positively charged amino group.

label: pleurite
Defs: The sclerite that is part of the pleuron.

label: retinal blood vessel morphogenesis
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a blood vessel of the retina over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

label: catecholamine transport
Defs: The directed movement of catecholamines, a group of physiologically important biogenic amines that possess a catechol (3,4-dihydroxyphenyl) nucleus and are derivatives of 3,4-dihydroxyphenylethylamine.

label: protein complex involved in cell-cell adhesion
Defs: Any protein complex that is capable of carrying out some part of the process of cell-cell adhesion.

label: negative regulation of gene expression
Defs: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene\'s coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product (protein or RNA).

label: horizontal plane
Defs: Anatomical plane that divides bilateral body into dorsal and ventral parts.

label: endocardium formation
Defs: Formation of the endocardium of the heart. The endocardium is an anatomical structure comprised of an endothelium and an extracellular matrix that forms the innermost layer of tissue of the heart, and lines the heart chambers.

label: asymmetric neuroblast division
Defs: The process resulting in the physical partitioning and separation of a neuroblast into two daughter cells with different developmental potentials.

label: stellate morphology
Defs: A cell morphology that inheres in neurons that have dendritic processes radiating from the cell body forming a star-like shape.

label: ADP-ribosyl cyclase/cyclic ADP-ribose hydrolase 1
Defs: An ADP-ribosyl cyclase that is a translation product of the human CD38 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: positive regulation of smooth muscle hypertrophy
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle hypertrophy.

label: regulation of phosphate metabolic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving phosphates.

label: chondrocyte differentiation involved in endochondral bone morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which a chondroblast acquires specialized structural and/or functional features of a chondrocyte that will contribute to the development of a bone. A chondrocyte is a polymorphic cell that forms cartilage.

label: pelvic appendage bud ectoderm
Defs: An unilaminar epithelium that surrounds a pelvic appendage bud.

label: spleen
Defs: The organ that functions to filter blood and to store red corpuscles and platelets.

label: myocoele
Defs: The cavity within a myotome.

label: hypopharynx
Defs: The conjunctiva of the insect head that is attached to the salivarium and to the oral foraminal conjunctiva.

label: cell adhesion
Defs: The attachment of a cell, either to another cell or to an underlying substrate such as the extracellular matrix, via cell adhesion molecules.

label: catalytic activity, acting on a glycoprotein
Defs: Catalysis of a biochemical reaction at physiological temperatures in which one of the substrates is a glycoprotein.

label: mislocalised radially
Defs: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being out of its usual or proper place, or position around a central point or axis.

label: Thy-1 membrane glycoprotein (mouse)
Defs: A Thy-1 membrane glycoprotein that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: membrane-spanning 4-domains subfamily A member 1
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human MS4A1 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: light purple
Defs: A color consisting of purple color and high brightness.

label: placenta development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the placenta over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The placenta is an organ of metabolic interchange between fetus and mother, partly of embryonic origin and partly of maternal origin.

label: tunica media of pulmonary trunk
Defs: Tunica media of artery which is continuous with the myocardium of right ventricle.[FMA].

label: obsolete consumption quality
Defs: A relational quality of occurrent inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s ability to consume a resource.

label: microtubule cytoskeleton organization
Defs: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising microtubules and their associated proteins.

label: stratified squamous epithelial cell of anal canal
Defs: A stratified squamous epithelial cell that is part of the anal canal.

label: decreased viscosity
Defs: A viscosity which relatively low.

label: elytral humerus
Defs: The region of cuticle on the antero-lateral region of the elytron.

label: organic acid
Defs: Any organic molecular entity that is acidic and contains carbon in covalent linkage.

label: cuticular carina
Defs: The protrusion on a sclerite that is elongated.

label: larynx mucous gland
Defs: A mucous gland that is part of a larynx [Automatically generated definition].

label: document
Defs: A collection of information content entities intended to be understood together as a whole

label: superior vena cava morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structure of superior vena cava generated and organized. The superior vena cava is a blood vessel that transports blood from the upper body to the heart.

label: cellular response to inorganic substance
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an inorganic substance stimulus.

label: unfused from
Defs: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being no longer merged with another entity.

label: epidermis development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the epidermis over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The epidermis is the outer epithelial layer of an animal, it may be a single layer that produces an extracellular material (e.g. the cuticle of arthropods) or a complex stratified squamous epithelium, as in the case of many vertebrate species.

label: receptivity
Defs: A behavioral quality which holds by virtue of whether the bearer exhibits the ability to receive another agentitive entity.

label: anatomical cluster
Defs: Anatomical group that has its parts adjacent to one another.

label: heterocycle biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of heterocyclic compounds, those with a cyclic molecular structure and at least two different atoms in the ring (or rings).

label: susceptibility toward
Defs: A quality inhering in an entity by virtue of the bearer\'s propensity to resist an external stimulus.

label: proper hepatic artery
Defs: The hepatic artery proper (also proper hepatic artery), arises from the common hepatic artery and runs alongside the portal vein and the common bile duct to form the portal triad. The hepatic artery proper gives off a small supraduodenal artery to the duodenal bulb. Then the right gastric artery comes off and runs to the left along the lesser curvature of the stomach to meet the left gastric artery, which is a branch of the celiac trunk. It subsequently gives off the cystic artery, which feeds the gallbladder, before bifurcating into the right and left hepatic arteries. Of note, the right and left hepatic arteries may demonstrate variant anatomy. A replaced right hepatic artery may arise from the superior mesenteric artery (SMA) and a replaced left hepatic artery may arise from the left gastric artery.

label: regulation of epithelial to mesenchymal transition
Defs: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of epithelial to mesenchymal transition. Epithelial to mesenchymal transition where an epithelial cell loses apical/basolateral polarity, severs intercellular adhesive junctions, degrades basement membrane components and becomes a migratory mesenchymal cell.

label: right cardiac chamber
Defs: Any chamber of the right side of the heart.

label: CD7 molecule
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human CD7 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: female gonad development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the female gonad over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

label: inferolateral tentorio-mandibular muscle
Defs: The cranio-mandibular muscle that extends between the anterior tentorial arm and the proximal-ventral margin of the insect mandible.

label: central nervous system gray matter layer
Defs: A layer of of the central nervous system that is part of gray matter.

label: parietal serous membrane
Defs: Serous membrane layer that lines to a body cavity.

label: axonemal microtubule
Defs: A microtubule in the axoneme of a eukaryotic cilium or flagellum; an axoneme contains nine modified doublet microtubules, which may or may not surround a pair of single microtubules.

label: aorta tunica intima
Defs: The innermost layer of the aorta, containing the endothelium and an inner elastic membrane.

label: insulin receptor signaling pathway
Defs: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the insulin receptor binding to insulin.

label: regulation of type B pancreatic cell apoptotic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of type B pancreatic cell apoptotic process.

label: aorta collagen fibril
Defs: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of aorta tissue that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity.

label: female germ-line stem cell asymmetric division
Defs: The self-renewing division of a germline stem cell in the female gonad, to produce a daughter stem cell and a daughter germ cell, which will divide to form the female gametes.

label: superficial
Defs: A spatial pattern inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being located near a surface.

label: face
Defs: A subdivision of the head that has as parts the layers deep to the surface of the anterior surface, including the mouth, eyes, and nose (when present). In vertebrates, this includes the facial skeleton and structures superficial to the facial skeleton (cheeks, mouth, eyeballs, skin of face, etc).

label: negative regulation of leukocyte apoptotic process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of leukocyte apoptotic process.

label: decayed
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s decomposition into component parts.

label: cellular_component
Defs: A location, relative to cellular compartments and structures, occupied by a macromolecular machine when it carries out a molecular function. There are two ways in which the gene ontology describes locations of gene products: (1) relative to cellular structures (e.g., cytoplasmic side of plasma membrane) or compartments (e.g., mitochondrion), and (2) the stable macromolecular complexes of which they are parts (e.g., the ribosome).

label: karyogamy
Defs: The creation of a single nucleus from multiple nuclei as a result of fusing the lipid bilayers that surround each nuclei.

label: normal susceptibility toward
Defs: A susceptibility toward an external stimulus which is relatively normal or average

label: glycoprotein metabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glycoproteins, a protein that contains covalently bound glycose (i.e. monosaccharide) residues; the glycose occurs most commonly as oligosaccharide or fairly small polysaccharide but occasionally as monosaccharide.

label: hemolymphoid system gland
Defs: A gland that is part of a hemolymphoid system [Automatically generated definition].

label: cellular divalent inorganic anion homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of divalent inorganic anions at the level of a cell.

label: positive regulation of bone development
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of bone development.

label: intestine
Defs: Segment of the alimentary canal extending from the stomach to the anus and, in humans and other mammals, consists of two segments, the small intestine and the large intestine.

label: trigeminal ganglion development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a trigeminal ganglion over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

label: retrograde trans-synaptic signaling
Defs: Cell-cell signaling from post to pre-synapse, across the synaptic cleft.

label: muscle of pelvic girdle
Defs: Any muscle organ that is part of a pelvic girdle [Automatically generated definition].

label: negative regulation of vascular associated smooth muscle cell migration
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vascular associated smooth muscle cell migration.

label: mesoderm
Defs: The middle germ layer of the embryo, between the endoderm and ectoderm.

label: axon ensheathment in central nervous system
Defs: The process in which a glial cell membrane closes around an axon in the central nervous system. This can be a myelinating or a non-myelinating neuron-glial interaction.

label: flavor
Defs: A quality of a physical entity inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer\'s molecules are being perceived by a taste and odorant receptors.

label: negative regulation of nuclear division
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of nuclear division, the partitioning of the nucleus and its genetic information.

label: integral component of synaptic membrane
Defs: The component of the synaptic membrane consisting of the gene products and protein complexes having at least some part of their peptide sequence embedded in the hydrophobic region of the membrane.

label: aorta morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of an aorta are generated and organized. An aorta is an artery that carries blood from the heart to other parts of the body.

label: sensillum placodeum
Defs: The seta that is flattened.

label: increased intensity
Defs: An intensity which is relatively high.

label: ventral pancreatic bud
Defs: Pancreatic bud that gives rise to the major pancreatic duct.

label: integrin alpha-M (mouse)
Defs: An integrin alpha-M that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: pharyngeal arch 2
Defs: The second pharyngeal arch will form the hyoid apparatus. The cranial neural crest cells that populate the second pharyngeal arch emerge primarily from rhombomere 4 and will form skeletal elements.

label: regulation of neural precursor cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of neural precursor cell proliferation.

label: hemolymphoid system
Defs: Anatomical cluster consisting of the hematopoietic system and the lymphoid system, or its analogs.

label: negative regulation of heart growth
Defs: Any process that decreases the rate or extent of heart growth. Heart growth is the increase in size or mass of the heart.

label: heterochronic
Defs: A quality of a single process inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s origin or development at an unusual time or out of the regular sequence.

label: decreased sensitivity to irradiation
Defs: A sensitivity to irradiation which is relatively low.

label: regular spatial pattern
Defs: A pattern quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having a repeatable or predictable placement.

label: negative regulation of leukocyte differentiation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of leukocyte differentiation.

label: lymphocyte proliferation
Defs: The expansion of a lymphocyte population by cell division.

label: biconcave
Defs: A concave quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s curving inward on both sides or surfaces.

label: molariform
Defs: A 3-D shape inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having an entity in the form of a molar tooth.

label: homopolysaccharide
Defs: Glycans composed of a single type of monosaccharide residue. They are named by replacing the ending \'-ose\' of the sugar by \'-an\'.

label: tentorio-frontal muscle
Defs: The insect cranio-antennal muscle that is attached to the tentorial bridge and the frons.

label: dicarboxylic acid dianion
Defs: A carboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of any dicarboxylic acid.

label: surface feature shape
Defs: A surface shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s shape of features present on its surface or outer shell.

label: negative regulation of tetrapyrrole metabolic process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of tetrapyrrole metabolic process.

label: sound frequency
Defs: The frequency of transmitted vibrations.

label: atrial septum development
Defs: The progression of the atrial septum over time, from its initial formation to the mature structure.

label: vacuole organization
Defs: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a vacuole.

label: viscus
Defs: An organ that is located within the body cavity (or in its extension, in the scrotum); it consists of organ parts that are embryologically derived from endoderm, splanchnic mesoderm or intermediate mesoderm; together with other organs, the viscus constitutes the respiratory, gastrointestinal, urinary, reproductive and immune systems, or is the central organ of the cardiovascular system. Examples: heart, lung, esophagus, kidney, ovary, spleen.

label: ambidextrous handedness
Defs: Handedness where the organism exhibits no overall dominance in the use of right or left hand or foot in the performance of tasks that require one hand or foot or a dominant hand or foot.

label: left pelvic girdle region
Defs: A pelvic girdle region that is in the left side of a multicellular organism.

label: duplicated
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being present in two copies.

label: neuron of the forebrain
Defs: A CNS neuron of the forebrain.

label: sodium ion binding
Defs: Binding to a sodium ion (Na+).

label: 3rd arch mesenchyme
Defs: Mesenchyme that is part of a pharyngeal arch 3.

label: anterior vena cava
Defs: A vein that carries deoxygenated blood from the upper half of the body into the right atrium of the heart.

label: regulation of extracellular matrix organization
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of extracellular matrix organization.

label: negative regulation of neuron death
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of neuron death.

label: synaptic signaling
Defs: Cell-cell signaling to, from or within a synapse.

label: small intestine
Defs: Subdivision of digestive tract that connects the stomach to the large intestine and is where much of the digestion and absorption of food takes place (with the exception of ruminants). The mammalian small intestine is long and coiled and can be differentiated histologically into: duodenum, jejunem, ileum[WP,cjm,Kardong].

label: tubulin binding
Defs: Binding to monomeric or multimeric forms of tubulin, including microtubules.

label: post-juvenile adult stage
Defs: The stage of being a sexually mature adult animal.

label: crescent-shaped
Defs: A shape quality inhering in a circular disk by virtue of the bearer\'s having a segment of another circle removed from its edge, so that what remains is a shape enclosed by two circular arcs of different diameters which intersect at two points (usually in such a manner that the enclosed shape does not include the center of the original circle).

label: cardiac pacemaker cell development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a pacemaker cell over time, from its formation to the mature state. Pacemaker cells are specialized cardiomyocytes that are responsible for regulating the timing of heart contractions.

label: response to endogenous stimulus
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus arising within the organism.

label: orthochromatic erythroblast
Defs: The final stage of the nucleated, immature erythrocyte, before nuclear loss. Typically the cytoplasm is described as acidophilic, but it still shows a faint polychromatic tint. The nucleus is small and initially may still have coarse, clumped chromatin, as in its precursor, the polychromatophilic erythroblast, but ultimately it becomes pyknotic, and appears as a deeply staining, blue-black, homogeneous structureless mass. The nucleus is often eccentric and sometimes lobulated.

label: subgenal ridge
Defs: The ridge of the head capsule that separates the gena and the subgena.

label: protein kinase activity
Defs: Catalysis of the phosphorylation of an amino acid residue in a protein, usually according to the reaction: a protein + ATP = a phosphoprotein + ADP.

label: organelle localization by membrane tethering
Defs: The process by which an organelle membrane interacts with another membrane via molecular tethers that physically bridge the two membranes and attach them to each other.

label: paramesonephric duct development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the paramesonephric duct over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Mullerian ducts (or paramesonephric ducts) are paired ducts of the embryo that run down the lateral sides of the urogenital ridge and terminate at the mullerian eminence in the primitive urogenital sinus. In the female, they will develop to form the fallopian tubes, uterus, cervix, and the upper portion of the vagina; in the male, they are lost. These ducts are made of tissue of mesodermal origin.

label: cardiac muscle tissue morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of cardiac muscle tissue are generated and organized.

label: cellular response to endogenous stimulus
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus arising within the organism.

label: cell junction
Defs: A cellular component that forms a specialized region of connection between two or more cells, or between a cell and the extracellular matrix, or between two membrane-bound components of a cell, such as flagella.

label: asymmetrically curved
Defs: A curvature quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being curved asymmetrically.

label: unicellular cuticular evagination
Defs: The cuticular evagination that corresponds to the evagination on the membrane of a single cell and not to the evagination of a cell layer.

label: ectodermal placode development
Defs: The progression of an ectodermal placode over time from its initial formation until its mature state. An ectodermal placode is a thickening of the ectoderm that is the primordium of many structures derived from the ectoderm.

label: 3rd arch ectoderm
Defs: An ectoderm that is part of a pharyngeal arch 3.

label: scirrhous
Defs: A hardness quality of being rigid and resistant to pressure and fibrous.

label: regulation of timing of cell differentiation
Defs: The process controlling the activation and/or rate at which relatively unspecialized cells acquire specialized features. Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of the XXX at a consistent predetermined time point during its development.

label: neuron apoptotic process
Defs: Any apoptotic process in a neuron, the basic cellular unit of nervous tissue. Each neuron consists of a body, an axon, and dendrites. Their purpose is to receive, conduct, and transmit impulses in the nervous system.

label: negative regulation of endothelial tube morphogenesis
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of endothelial tube morphogenesis.

label: lens morphogenesis in camera-type eye
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the lens are generated and organized. The lens is a transparent structure in the eye through which light is focused onto the retina. An example of this process is found in Mus musculus.

label: process profile
Defs: b is a process_profile =Def. there is some process c such that b process_profile_of c (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [093-002])

label: peripheral region
Defs: Anatomical region peripherally located on the body or body part.

label: tunica media of artery
Defs: A tunica media that is part of a artery.

label: retinal progenitor cell
Defs: A multi-fate stem cell that can give rise to different retinal cell types including rod and cone cells.

label: increased force
Defs: A force which relative high.

label: cerebral cortex endothelial cell
Defs: Endothelial cells forming the walls of the capillaries within the cerebral cortex.

label: coating
Defs: A texture quality that exists through a liquid cover on the surface of the bearer.

label: lens cortex
Defs: Tissue that surrounds the lens nucleus.

label: dendritic cell chemotaxis
Defs: The movement of a dendritic cell in response to an external stimulus.

label: endoderm of buccopharyngeal membrane
Defs: An endoderm that is part of a buccopharyngeal membrane.

label: regulation of macromolecule metabolic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving macromolecules, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass.

label: indole-containing compound biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of compounds that contain an indole (2,3-benzopyrrole) skeleton.

label: regulation of translation at presynapse, modulating synaptic transmission
Defs: Any process that modulates synaptic transmission by regulating translation occurring at the presynapse.

label: availability section
Defs: A part of a document about a resource described in the document, e.g. software, that describes where and/or how that resource can be obtained.

label: decreased spatial extent of a process
Defs: A spatial distribution of a process in which the process occupies a smaller length, area, or volume than the reference process. For example, heterochromatin may form over a shorter length of a chromosome in a mutant than in wild type.

label: decreased branchiness
Defs: Branchiness quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of decreasing the degree to which there are subdivisions or offshoots in a bearer entity.

label: gallbladder fibroblast
Defs: Any fibroblast that is part of a gallbladder.

label: respiratory system lamina propria
Defs: A lamina propria that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

label: negative regulation of morphogenesis of an epithelium
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of morphogenesis of an epithelium.

label: bone tissue
Defs: Skeletal tissue with a collagen-rich extracellular matrix vascularized, mineralized with hydroxyapatite and typically including osteocytes located in lacunae that communicate with one another by cell processes (in canaliculi). Bone is deposited by osteoblasts.

label: ciliated columnar oviduct epithelium
Defs: A ciliated columnar epithelium that is part of a oviduct.

label: pleural fluid
Defs: Transudate contained in the pleural cavity.

label: profurca-prophragmal muscle
Defs: The dorsoventral thoracic muscle that extends between the profurca and the lateral region of the prophragma.

label: regulation of fertilization
Defs: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of fertilization. Fertilization is the union of gametes of opposite sexes during the process of sexual reproduction to form a zygote. It involves the fusion of the gametic nuclei (karyogamy) and cytoplasm (plasmogamy).

label: midsagittal plane
Defs: Sagittal plane that divides bilateral body into equal left and right parts.

label: spirally fractured
Defs: A fractured quality that occurs when torque (a rotating force) is applied along the axis of a bone.

label: regulation of heart growth
Defs: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of heart growth. Heart growth is the increase in size or mass of the heart.

label: positive regulation of bone resorption
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of bone resorption.

label: anatomical system
Defs: Multicellular, connected anatomical structure that has multiple organs as parts and whose parts work together to achieve some shared function.

label: synaptic signaling via neuropeptide
Defs: Cell-cell signaling to or from a synapse, mediated by a peptide.

label: pectoral complex muscle
Defs: A muscle of a pectoral girdle, pectoral fin or anterior limb.

label: sequential hermaphrodite
Defs: A hermaphroditic quality that inheres in a population or organism where an organism changes is a different sexes during different life stages.

label: differentiated
Defs: A cellular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of its stable specialization to a particular cell type.

label: positive regulation of small intestine smooth muscle contraction
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of small intestine smooth muscle contraction.

label: regulation of monocyte antigen processing and presentation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of monocyte antigen processing and presentation.

label: skeletal muscle organ
Defs: A muscle organ that consists of skeletal muscle tissue ensheathed in epimysium, that develops from myotome and that is innervated by some somatic motor neuron. Skeletal muscles are typically attached (via a tendon) to a bone but there are exceptions (e.g. intrinsic tongue muscles).

label: salivary sclerite
Defs: The sclerite of the salivarium.

label: myelination
Defs: The process in which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons. Oligodendrocytes in the brain and spinal cord and Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system wrap axons with compact layers of their plasma membrane. Adjacent myelin segments are separated by a non-myelinated stretch of axon called a node of Ranvier.

label: positive regulation of protein-containing complex disassembly
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein complex disassembly, the disaggregation of a protein complex into its constituent components.

label: displaced to
Defs: An angular placement quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being changed in position in relation to another entity.

label: negative regulation of excitatory synapse pruning
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of excitatory synapse pruning.

label: organic hydroxy compound metabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving organic hydroxy compound.

label: lytic vacuole membrane
Defs: The lipid bilayer surrounding a lytic vacuole and separating its contents from the cytoplasm of the cell.

label: somatic stem cell
Defs: A stem cell that can give rise to cell types of the body other than those of the germ-line.

label: digestive tract morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the digestive tract are generated and organized. The digestive tract is the anatomical structure through which food passes and is processed.

label: transmural
Defs: Extending through or affecting the entire thickness of the wall of an organ or cavity or boundary.

label: transmembrane collagen trimer
Defs: Any collagen trimer that passes through a lipid bilayer membrane.

label: temporally extended
Defs: A quality of a process which ends later than the natural end time.

label: cell-cell junction disassembly
Defs: The disaggregation of a cell-cell junction into its constituent components.

label: abnormal
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s deviation from normal or average.

label: desaturated yellow
Defs: A color consisting of yellow hue and low saturation.

label: negative regulation of nucleobase-containing compound transport
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: negative regulation of cell junction assembly
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell junction assembly.

label: increased adhesivity
Defs: A adhesivity which is relatively high.

label: negative regulation of translational termination
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of translational termination.

label: glucagon secretion
Defs: The regulated release of glucagon from secretory granules in the A (alpha) cells of the pancreas (islets of Langerhans).

label: negative regulation of developmental process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of development, the biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of an organism over time from an initial condition (e.g. a zygote, or a young adult) to a later condition (e.g. a multicellular animal or an aged adult).

label: mesofurco-metafurcal muscle
Defs: The insect thoracic muscle that extends between the mesofurca and the metafurca.

label: undifferentiated
Defs: A cellular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of having not yet acquired a special structure of function.

label: hydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid
Defs: Any member of the class of 5beta-cholanic acids carrying at least one hydroxy group at unspecified position.

label: nuclear factor NF-kappa-B p100 subunit
Defs: A transcription factor NF-kappa-B subunit that is a translation product of the human NFKB2 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: hydrogencarbonate
Defs: The carbon oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from carbonic acid.

label: transitional anatomical structure
Defs: An embryonic anatomical entity that will turn into one or more other anatomical entities, perhaps with other anatomical entities, later in development.

label: acceleration
Defs: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the rate of change of the bearer\'s velocity in either speed or direction.

label: poststernite
Defs: The part of the sternum that is attached to the posterior margin of the spinasternum.

label: cerebral hemisphere white matter
Defs: White matter that is part of a cerebral hemisphere.

label: skeletal joint
Defs: Anatomical cluster that consists of two or more adjacent skeletal structures, which may be interconnected by various types of tissue[VSAO].

label: fluctuating
Defs: Recurrent and often more or less cyclic alteration.

label: aqueous humor of eyeball
Defs: A thick watery refractive medium that fills the space between the lens and the cornea[WP].

label: positive regulation of cell maturation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell maturation.

label: dendrite membrane
Defs: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a dendrite.

label: eye morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the eye are generated and organized.

label: gamete generation
Defs: The generation and maintenance of gametes in a multicellular organism. A gamete is a haploid reproductive cell.

label: positive regulation of smooth muscle cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of smooth muscle cell proliferation.

label: right lung morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which anatomical structures of the right lung are generated and organized.

label: female
Defs: A biological sex quality inhering in an individual or a population that only produces gametes that can be fertilised by male gametes.

label: vein of lower lip
Defs: The inferior labial vein is the vein receiving blood from the lower lip.

label: blood vessel endothelial cell
Defs: An endothelial cell that lines the vasculature.

label: negative regulation of meiotic nuclear division
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of meiosis.

label: microtubule-based movement
Defs: A microtubule-based process that results in the movement of organelles, other microtubules, or other cellular components.  Examples include motor-driven movement along microtubules and movement driven by polymerization or depolymerization of microtubules.

label: tetrapyrrole biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways leading to the formation of tetrapyrroles, natural pigments containing four pyrrole rings joined by one-carbon units linking position 2 of one pyrrole ring to position 5 of the next.

label: positive regulation of cardiac conduction
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac conduction.

label: glucose homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of glucose within an organism or cell.

label: irregular bone
Defs: The irregular bones are bones which, from their peculiar form, cannot be grouped as long bone, short bone, flat bone or sesamoid bone. Irregular bones serve various purposes in the body, such as protection of nervous tissue, affording multiple anchor points for skeletal muscle attachment (as with the sacrum), and maintaining pharynx and trachea support, and tongue attachment (such as the hyoid bone). They consist of cancellous tissue enclosed within a thin layer of compact bone. The irregular bones are: the vertebrC&, sacrum, coccyx, temporal, sphenoid, ethmoid, zygomatic, maxilla, mandible, palatine, inferior nasal concha, and hyoid.

label: nucleated
Defs: A nucleate quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having one or more nucleus.

label: ammonium excretion
Defs: The elimination of ammonium ions from an excretory cell.

label: response to radiation
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an electromagnetic radiation stimulus. Electromagnetic radiation is a propagating wave in space with electric and magnetic components. These components oscillate at right angles to each other and to the direction of propagation.

label: carboxylic acid dianion
Defs: Any dianion containing at least one carboxy group.

label: right subclavian artery
Defs: The subclavian artery that supplies the right pectoral appendage.

label: pin-like
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being thin and lacking outgrowths.

label: ploidy
Defs: A cellular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s number of homologous sets of chromosomes in the nucleus or primary chromosome-containing compartment of the cell, each set essentially coding for all the biological traits of the organism.

label: embryonic skeletal muscle fiber
Defs: A skeletal muscle fiber found in an embryo. In mammalian embryos, skeletal muscle expresses myosin heavy chain-embryonic (MyHC-emb, encoded by the MYH3 gene), which regulates skeletal muscle development.

label: anterograde axonal transport
Defs: The directed movement of organelles or molecules along microtubules from the cell body toward the cell periphery in nerve cell axons.

label: regulation of SA node cell action potential
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination in an SA node cardiac myocyte. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

label: macrophage migration
Defs: The orderly movement of a macrophage from one site to another.

label: neurogliaform cell
Defs: An interneuron that has spider-like appearance with a small round soma, a large number (7-10) of short, smooth, or slightly beaded primary dendrites that give rise to only a few secondary branches, and a branched axon that establishes a dense axonal mesh with thin shafts.
