Defs: A leukocyte with a single non-segmented nucleus in the mature form.

label: positive regulation of morphogenesis of an epithelium
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of morphogenesis of an epithelium.

label: lymphocyte mediated immunity
Defs: Any process involved in the carrying out of an immune response by a lymphocyte.

label: locus ceruleus
Defs: The locus ceruleus is a dense cluster of neurons within the dorsorostral pons. This nucleus is the major location of neurons that release norepinephrine throughout the brain, and is responsible for physiological responses to stress and panic[GO]. Bluish region in the superior angle of the fourth ventricle floor, corresponding to melanin-like pigmented nerve cells which lie lateral to the ponto-mesencephalic central gray (griseum centrale). It is also known as nucleus pigmentosus pontis[GAID].

label: normal temperature
Defs: A temperature which is relatively normal or average

label: zone of stomach
Defs: A division of the stomach. The stomach can be divided based on mucosal histology (glandular epithelium and gastric glands) and the relative position and type of gastric gland.

label: cellular trivalent inorganic anion homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of trivalent inorganic anions at the level of a cell.

label: positive regulation of heart growth
Defs: Any process that increases the rate or extent of heart growth. Heart growth is the increase in size or mass of the heart.

label: intraciliary transport involved in cilium assembly
Defs: The bidirectional movement of large protein complexes along microtubules within a cilium that contributes to cilium assembly.

label: stomach muscularis externa
Defs: The smooth muscle layer of the stomach wall that functions to churn and mix food and gastric secretions as well as to move food along the digestive tract to the intestines.

label: dendritic spine membrane
Defs: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a dendritic spine.

label: multicellular organism
Defs: Anatomical structure that is an individual member of a species and consists of more than one cell.

label: iris nerve
Defs: Any nerve that innervates the iris.

label: response to stress
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a disturbance in organismal or cellular homeostasis, usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

label: regulation of transmembrane transporter activity
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of transmembrane transporter activity.

label: neuroblast (sensu Vertebrata)
Defs: A cell that will develop into a neuron often after a migration phase.

label: negative regulation of monocyte antigen processing and presentation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of monocyte antigen processing and presentation.

label: peripheral nervous system axon ensheathment
Defs: The process in which a Schwann cell membrane closes around an axon in the peripheral nervous system. This can be a myelinating or a non-myelinating neuron-glial interaction.

label: frequency
Defs: A physical quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the number of the bearer\'s repetitive actions in a particular time.

label: positive regulation of nuclear division
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of nuclear division, the partitioning of the nucleus and its genetic information.

label: negative regulation of smooth muscle cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of smooth muscle cell proliferation.

label: negative regulation of binding
Defs: Any process that stops or reduces the rate or extent of binding, the selective interaction of a molecule with one or more specific sites on another molecule.

label: endometrial blood vessel
Defs: A blood vessel that is part of a endometrium.

label: protein c-Fos (mouse)
Defs: A protein c-Fos that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: regulation of G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway.

label: signal transduction involved in cellular response to ammonium ion
Defs: Any signal transduction that is involved in cellular response to ammonium ion.

label: acidophilic
Defs: An affinity inhering in an anatomical structure by virtue of the bearer exhibiting a molecular interaction for acidic dyes under specific pH conditions.

label: diameter
Defs: A length quality which is equal to the length of any straight line segment that passes through the center of a circle and whose endpoints are on the circular boundary.

label: carbamic acid
Defs: A one-carbon compound that is ammonia in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by a carboxy group. Although carbamic acid derivatives are common, carbamic acid itself has never been synthesised.

label: positive regulation of meiotic nuclear division
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of meiosis.

label: normal
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s exhibiting no deviation from normal or average.

label: regulation of receptor binding
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a protein or other molecule binding to a receptor.

label: red bone marrow
Defs: The red vascular substance consisting of connective tissue and blood vessels, containing primitive blood cells, macrophages, megakaryocytes, and fat cells. Red marrow is found in the cavities of many bones. It manufactures and releases leukocytes and erythrocytes into the bloodstream.

label: negative regulation of neural precursor cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of neural precursor cell proliferation.

label: cellular component disassembly
Defs: A cellular process that results in the breakdown of a cellular component.

label: positive regulation of translational termination
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of translational termination.

label: pectoral appendage bud
Defs: A limb bud that develops into a forelimb or pectoral fin.

label: positive regulation of developmental process
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of development, the biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of an organism over time from an initial condition (e.g. a zygote, or a young adult) to a later condition (e.g. a multicellular animal or an aged adult).

label: gula
Defs: The sclerite on the ventral region of the head capsule that is limited laterally by the gular ridges, posteriorly by the foramen occipitale and anteriorly by the submentum.

label: sepal-like
Defs: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s similarity to the appearance of a sepal,

label: regulation of neuronal action potential
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination in a neuron. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

label: facial artery
Defs: A branch of the external carotid artery that supplies structures of the face. [WP,unvetted].

label: regulation of endothelial cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of endothelial cell differentiation.

label: mucosa of lip
Defs: A mucosa that is part of a lip region [Automatically generated definition].

label: regulation of melanosome transport
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of melanosome transport.

label: insulin receptor activity
Defs: Combining with insulin receptor ligand and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.

label: increased fluorescence
Defs: A fluorescence which is higher than normal.

label: protein localization to organelle
Defs: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within an organelle.

label: system
Defs: A material entity consisting of multiple components that are causally integrated.

label: regulation of axonogenesis
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of axonogenesis, the generation of an axon, the long process of a neuron.

label: camera-type eye morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the eye are generated and organized. The camera-type eye is an organ of sight that receives light through an aperture and focuses it through a lens, projecting it on a photoreceptor field.

label: retinal bipolar neuron differentiation
Defs: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a bipolar cell, the last neuron to be generated in the retina.

label: vacuolar transmembrane transport
Defs: The process in which a solute is transported from one side of the vacuolar membrane to the other.

label: positive regulation of insulin secretion
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin.

label: anteverted
Defs: An oriented quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s axis being positioned forward.

label: regulation of cardiac muscle cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle cell differentiation.

label: food preservative
Defs: Substances which are added to food in order to prevent decomposition caused by  microbial growth or by undesirable chemical changes.

label: negative regulation of neural retina development
Defs: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of neural retina development, the progression of the neural retina over time from its initial formation to the mature structure. The neural retina is the part of the retina that contains neurons and photoreceptor cells.

label: cation transmembrane transporter activity
Defs: Enables the transfer of cation from one side of a membrane to the other.

label: ion
Defs: A molecular entity having a net electric charge.

label: pnictogen molecular entity
Defs: A p-block molecular entity containing any pnictogen.

label: negative regulation of angiogenesis
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of angiogenesis.

label: male
Defs: A biological sex quality inhering in an individual or a population whose sex organs contain only male gametes.

label: negative regulation of extracellular matrix organization
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of extracellular matrix organization.

label: receptor-type tyrosine-protein kinase FLT3
Defs: A CSF-1/PDGF receptor-type tyrosine-protein kinase that is a translation product of the human FLT3 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: actomyosin
Defs: Any complex of actin, myosin, and accessory proteins.

label: microtubule depolymerization
Defs: The removal of tubulin heterodimers from one or both ends of a microtubule.

label: chemical role
Defs: A role played by the molecular entity or part thereof within a chemical context.

label: hindgut morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the hindgut are generated and organized.

label: sensitivity toward
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s disposition to detect or perceive external stimulation.

label: negative regulation of anion transmembrane transport
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of anion transmembrane transport.

label: megakaryocyte progenitor cell
Defs: The earliest cytologically identifiable precursor in the thrombocytic series. This cell is capable of endomitosis and lacks expression of hematopoieitic lineage markers (lin-negative).

label: regulation of dendritic spine morphogenesis
Defs: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of dendritic spine morphogenesis, the process in which the anatomical structures of a dendritic spine are generated and organized. A dendritic spine is a protrusion from a dendrite and a specialized subcellular compartment involved in synaptic transmission.

label: alobate
Defs: A surface feature shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s not having undulating edges forming lobes.

label: reproductive system development
Defs: The progression of the reproductive system over time from its formation to the mature structure. The reproductive system consists of the organs that function in reproduction.

label: case report textual entity
Defs: A textual entity that expresses a detailed account of a portion of the medical history for a specific patient.

label: myeloid dendritic cell differentiation involved in immune response
Defs: The process in which an immature myeloid dendritic cell acquires the specialized features of a mature myeloid dendritic cell as part of an immune response.

label: abrased
Defs: A texture quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of a portion of the bearer\'s surface being scraped away.

label: glucose transmembrane transporter activity
Defs: Enables the transfer of the hexose monosaccharide glucose from one side of a membrane to the other.

label: abdominal tergite VII-abdominal tergite VIII conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva of the insect abdomen that connects the abdominal tergite VII and the abdominal tergite VIII.

label: negative regulation of cell projection organization
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a process involved in the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cell projections.

label: open anatomical space
Defs: An anatomical space with at least one opening to another space or the exterior.

label: smooth muscle cell of large intestine
Defs: A smooth muscle cell that is part of the large intestine.

label: pharyngeal pouch
Defs: An internal pocketing of pharyngeal endoderm that contacts a region of ectoderm (a pharyngeal cleft) and interdigitates in the anterior and posterior directions with the pharyngeal arches.

label: epithelium of small intestine
Defs: An epithelium that is part of a small intestine [Automatically generated definition].

label: acceptor
Defs: A molecular entity that can accept an electron, a pair of electrons, an atom or a group from another molecular entity.

label: muscular coat of digestive tract
Defs: A muscular coat that is part of a digestive tract.

label: 1st arch mandibular mesenchyme from neural crest
Defs: Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a 1st arch mandibular mesenchyme.

label: intestinal epithelium
Defs: Epithelial layer that lines the intestine.

label: chitin-based cuticle
Defs: A cuticular covering that is composed primarily of chitin. The main structural component of arthropod cuticle is a polysaccharide, chitin, composed of N-acetylglucosamine units, together with proteins and lipids[WP].

label: positive regulation of dendritic cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of dendritic cell differentiation.

label: actinodromous
Defs: A branched quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having three or more primary branches diverging radially from a single point.

label: foramen occipitale
Defs: The foramen of the head capsule that connects with the neck membrane and is divided by the tentorial bridge into alaforamen and neuroforamen.

label: cortical intermediate zone
Defs: The region of the developing mammalian cortex that extends between the ventricular zone and the cortical plate (CP); normally, the IZ is a region of tangential migration of cells, and at midgestation, the lower part of the IZ develops into the subventricular zone.

label: Kit-positive erythroid progenitor cell
Defs: An erythroid progenitor cell is Kit-positive, Ly6A-negative, CD41-negative, CD127-negative, and CD123-negative. This cell type is also described as being lin-negative, Kit-positive, CD150-negative, CD41-negative, CD105-positive, and FcgR-negative.

label: agonist
Defs: Substance which binds to cell receptors normally responding to naturally occurring substances and which produces a response of its own.

label: phrenic vein
Defs: The veins that run parallel to the phrenic arteries which include the two superior and two inferior phrenic veins.

label: fasciculation
Defs: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer forms a bundle of anatomical fibers, as of muscle or nerve.

label: pedicellar-first flagellomeral conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva of the antenna that connects the pedicellus and the first flagellomere.

label: chordate pharynx
Defs: A portion of the respiratory and digestive tracts; its distal limit is the superior part of the esophagus and it connects the nasal and oral cavities with the esophagus and larynx; it contains the valleculae and the pyriform recesses; its upper limits are the nasal cavity and cranial base.[FEED].

label: regulation of response to biotic stimulus
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of a response to biotic stimulus.

label: negative regulation of embryonic development
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of embryonic development.

label: cellular response to acetate
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an acetate stimulus.

label: lateral pronotal carina
Defs: The carina of the pronotum that separates the pronotal disc from the hypomeron.

label: molar volume
Defs: A volume quality inhering in a homogeneous substance containing 6.02 x 1023 atoms or molecules by virtue of the amount of 3-dimensional space it occupies.

label: CD33 molecule
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human CD33 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: neural fold formation
Defs: The process in which the neural fold is formed. The edges of the neural plate thicken and move up to form a U-shaped structure called the neural groove.

label: pharyngeal arch 6
Defs: The 6th pharyngeal arch. contributes to the development of the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles.

label: striated muscle cell proliferation
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of striated muscle cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population. Striated muscles contain fibers that are divided by transverse bands into striations, and cardiac and skeletal muscle are types of striated muscle.

label: nuclear membrane fusion involved in karyogamy
Defs: The joining of 2 or more lipid bilayer membranes that surround the nucleus during the creation of a single nucleus from multiple nuclei.

label: dark violet
Defs: A color consisting of violet hue and low brightness.

label: inflexible
Defs: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s inability of being turned, bowed, or twisted without breaking.

label: cell proliferation in hindbrain
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population in the hindbrain.

label: myocardial endocrine cell of atrium
Defs: A myocardial endocrine cell that is part of the atrium.

label: postcranial axial skeleton
Defs: The postcranial subdivision of skeleton structural components forming the long axis of the vertebrate body; in Danio, consisting of the notochord, vertebrae, ribs, supraneurals, intermuscular bones, and unpaired median fins; in human consists of the bones of the vertebral column, the thoracic cage and the pelvis[ZFA+FMA].

label: neurogliaform morphology
Defs: A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have a small round soma, a large number of short, smooth, or slightly beaded primary dendrites that give rise to only a few secondary branches, and a branched axon that establishes a dense axonal mesh with thin shafts.

label: apatite
Defs: A phosphate mineral with the general formula Ca5(PO4)3X where X = OH, F or Cl.

label: inner cell mass derived epiblast
Defs: An embryonic structure that is derived from the inner cell mass and lies above the hypoblast and gives rise to the three primary germ layers.

label: muscle hypertrophy
Defs: The muscle system process that results in enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of a muscle organ due to an increase in the size of its muscle cells. Physiological hypertrophy is a normal process during development (it stops in cardiac muscle after adolescence) and can also be brought on in response to demand. In athletes cardiac and skeletal muscles undergo hypertrophy stimulated by increasing muscle activity on exercise. Smooth muscle cells in the uterus undergo hypertrophy during pregnancy.

label: cell migration involved in coronary vasculogenesis
Defs: The orderly movement of a cell from one site to another that will contribute to the differentiation of an endothelial cell that will form the blood vessels of the heart.

label: integumental taste bud
Defs: A taste bud that is located external to the digestive tube, on the head or body, as found in species such as goldfish.

label: skin mucus
Defs: A mucous secretion that is produced by glands in the epidermis.

label: variability of rate
Defs: A variability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer exhibits rate variation or change.

label: pelvic appendage cartilage tissue
Defs: A cartilage tissue that is part of a pelvic appendage.

label: red brown
Defs: A color consisting of red and brown hue.

label: institutional identification
Defs: A textual entity intended to identify a particular institution

label: positive regulation of nucleobase-containing compound transport
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: wetness
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer\'s being covered by a liquid.

label: intracellular organelle
Defs: Organized structure of distinctive morphology and function, occurring within the cell. Includes the nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, vacuoles, vesicles, ribosomes and the cytoskeleton. Excludes the plasma membrane.

label: smooth muscle contractile fiber
Defs: The contractile fiber of smooth muscle cells.

label: smooth muscle cell chemotaxis
Defs: The directed movement of a smooth muscle cell in response to an external stimulus.

label: negative regulation of transmembrane transport
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a solute from one side of a membrane to the other.

label: regulation of glucagon secretion
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of glucagon.

label: progenetic growth
Defs: A paedomorphic growth quality which is due to an earlier offset.

label: metaplastic
Defs: A cellular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of having changed from one fully differentiated state into another.

label: anterograde dendritic transport of neurotransmitter receptor complex
Defs: The directed movement of a neurotransmitter receptor complex along microtubules in nerve cell dendrites towards the postsynapse.

label: heterocyclic compound binding
Defs: Binding to heterocyclic compound.

label: journal article
Defs: A report that is published in a journal.

label: laterally compressed
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being flattened along transverse axis.

label: salivarium
Defs: The conjunctiva in the head capsule that forms a pouch between the hypopharynx and the labium and bears the exocrine gland duct.

label: mucus
Defs: Mucus is a bodily fluid consisting of a slippery secretion of the lining of the mucous membranes in the body. It is a viscous colloid containing antiseptic enzymes (such as lysozyme) and immunoglobulins. Mucus is produced by goblet cells in the mucous membranes that cover the surfaces of the membranes. It is made up of mucins and inorganic salts suspended in water.

label: neural crest cell migration involved in heart formation
Defs: The characteristic movement of a cell from the dorsal ridge of the neural tube towards the heart and that contributes to heart formation.

label: chondrocyte development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a chondrocyte over time, from its commitment to its mature state. Chondrocyte development does not include the steps involved in committing a chondroblast to a chondrocyte fate.

label: parasympathetic nervous system
Defs: The parasympathetic nervous system is one of the two divisions of the vertebrate autonomic nervous system. Parasympathetic nerves emerge cranially as pre ganglionic fibers from oculomotor, facial, glossopharyngeal and vagus and from the sacral region of the spinal cord. Most neurons are cholinergic and responses are mediated by muscarinic receptors. The parasympathetic system innervates, for example: salivary glands, thoracic and abdominal viscera, bladder and genitalia[GO].

label: labyrinthine layer development
Defs: The process in which the labyrinthine layer of the placenta progresses, from its formation to its mature state.

label: squircle
Defs: A shape with properties between those of a square and those of a circle.

label: sarcomere organization
Defs: The myofibril assembly process that results in the organization of muscle actomyosin into sarcomeres. The sarcomere is the repeating unit of a myofibril in a muscle cell, composed of an array of overlapping thick and thin filaments between two adjacent Z discs.

label: positive regulation of glucose transmembrane transport
Defs: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of glucose transport across a membrane. Glucose transport is the directed movement of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: posterior to
Defs: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being located toward the rear of an organism relative to another entity.

label: blood vessel endothelial cell migration
Defs: The orderly movement of an endothelial cell into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels during angiogenesis.

label: ectodermal cell differentiation
Defs: The process in which relatively unspecialized cells acquire specialized structural and/or functional features of an ectodermal cell. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a cell to a specific fate.

label: lung field
Defs: A specific region of the foregut into the area in which the lung will develop.

label: superior mesenteric vein
Defs: In anatomy, the superior mesenteric vein (SMV) is a blood vessel that drains blood from the small intestine. At its termination behind the neck of the pancreas, the SMV combines with the splenic vein to form the hepatic portal vein. The SMV lies to the right of the similarly named artery, the superior mesenteric artery, which originates from the abdominal aorta. [WP,unvetted].

label: retinal bipolar neuron
Defs: A bipolar neuron found in the retina and having connections with photoreceptors cells and neurons in the inner plexiform layer.

label: thoracic cavity vein
Defs: A vein that is part of a thoracic cavity [Automatically generated definition].

label: trans-synaptic signaling by neuropeptide, modulating synaptic transmission
Defs: Cell-cell signaling between presynapse and postsynapse, via the vesicular release and reception of neuropeptide molecules, that modulates the synaptic transmission properties of the synapse.

label: retinal bipolar morphology
Defs: A cell morphology that inheres in retinal neurons which have two principal fibres, an axon and a dendrite, that emerge from opposite end the soma.

label: semi erect
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being partially upright in position or posture.

label: mass density
Defs: A physical quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of some influence is exerted by the bearer\'s mass per unit size.

label: metasterno-abdominal sternite I conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva between the insect thorax and the insect abdomen that connects the posterior margin of the metasterum to the anterior margin of the abdominal sternite I.

label: tetrapyrrole catabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways leading to the breakdown of tetrapyrroles, natural pigments containing four pyrrole rings joined by one-carbon units linking position 2 of one pyrrole ring to position 5 of the next.

label: regulation of skeletal muscle fiber differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle fiber differentiation.

label: epibranchial ganglion
Defs: Cranial ganglion which develops from an epibranchial placode.

label: negative regulation of smooth muscle tissue development
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle tissue development.

label: normal perimeter
Defs: A perimeter which is relatively normal or average

label: multipolar neuron
Defs: A neuron with three or more neurites, usually an axon and multiple dendrites.

label: length unit
Defs: A unit which is a standard measure of the distance between two points.

label: haploid
Defs: A ploidy quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s containing a single set of homologous chromosomes.

label: positive regulation of cardiac muscle tissue growth
Defs: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle growth.

label: fibroblast
Defs: A connective tissue cell which secretes an extracellular matrix rich in collagen and other macromolecules. Flattened and irregular in outline with branching processes; appear fusiform or spindle-shaped.

label: mineralized skeletal tissue
Defs: Skeletal tissue that is mineralized.

label: references section
Defs: A part of a document that has citations as parts

label: epithelium of right lung
Defs: An epithelium that is part of a right lung [Automatically generated definition].

label: bronchiole
Defs: The conducting airway of the lungs found terminal to the bronchi; these structures contain neither cartilage nor mucous-secreting glands; the epithelium of the bronchioles becomes thinner with each branching.

label: sugar transmembrane transporter activity
Defs: Enables the transfer of a sugar from one side of a membrane to the other. A sugar is any member of a class of sweet, water-soluble, crystallizable carbohydrates, which are the monosaccharides and smaller oligosaccharides.

label: cell projection
Defs: A prolongation or process extending from a cell, e.g. a flagellum or axon.

label: lumen of duodenum
Defs: An anatomical space that is part of a duodenum.

label: proximal-distal gradient
Defs: Anatomical gradient that is distributed along the proximal-distal axis.

label: immobile relative to
Defs: Immobility relative to a second entity.

label: left side of
Defs: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being located on left side of from the a another entity.

label: intraciliary transport particle
Defs: A nonmembrane-bound oligomeric protein complex that participates in bidirectional transport of molecules (cargo) along axonemal microtubules.

label: facial vein
Defs: The anterior facial vein (facial vein) commences at the side of the root of the nose, and is a direct continuation of the angular vein where it also receives a small nasal branch. It lies behind the facial artery and follows a less tortuous course. It receives blood from the external palatine vein before it either joins the anterior branch of the retromandibular vein to form the common facial vein, or drains directly into the internal jugular vein. [WP,unvetted].

label: sinus venosus development
Defs: The progression of the sinus venosus over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The sinus venosus is a heart chamber attached to the atrium on the venous side of the embryonic heart.

label: increased affinity
Defs: An affinity which is relatively high.

label: chordal neural plate
Defs: The portion of neural plate posterior to the mid-hindbrain junction.

label: presumptive mesoderm
Defs: Presumptive structure of the blastula that will develop into mesoderm.

label: histogram
Defs:
A histogram is a report graph which is a statistical description of a
distribution in terms of occurrence frequencies of different event classes.

label: regulation of vascular associated smooth muscle cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of vascular smooth muscle cell proliferation.

label: appendage blood vessel
Defs: A blood vessel that is part of a limb/fin.

label: positive regulation of muscle tissue development
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of muscle tissue development.

label: killer cell lectin-like receptor subfamily B member 1C
Defs: A KLRB1-like protein that is a translation product of the mouse Klrb1c gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: cardiac skeleton
Defs: Dense connective tissue that separates the atria from the ventricles and provides physical support for the heart.

label: alimentary part of gastrointestinal system
Defs: The part of the digestive system that excludes the hepatobiliary system.

label: posteroventral to
Defs: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being located toward the rear and abdomen of an organism relative to another entity.

label: vertex
Defs: The dorsal region of the head capsule that surrounds the coronal suture, and is connected laterally to the genae.

label: regulation of defecation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of defecation.

label: stomach development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the stomach over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The stomach is an expanded region of the vertebrate alimentary tract that serves as a food storage compartment and digestive organ.

label: establishment of RNA localization
Defs: The directed movement of RNA to a specific location.

label: retinal rod cell
Defs: One of the two photoreceptor cell types of the vertebrate retina. In rods the photopigment is in stacks of membranous disks separate from the outer cell membrane. Rods are more sensitive to light than cones, but rod mediated vision has less spatial and temporal resolution than cone vision.

label: sensory receptor cell
Defs: A cell that is capable of detection of a stimulus involved in sensory perception.

label: gastric acid secretion
Defs: The regulated release of gastric acid (hydrochloric acid) by parietal or oxyntic cells during digestion.

label: smooth muscle cell proliferation
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of smooth muscle cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

label: peritoneal cavity
Defs: Anatomical cavity bounded by visceral and parietal peritoneum.

label: positive regulation of keratinocyte migration
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of keratinocyte migration.

label: positive regulation of myeloid dendritic cell cytokine production
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of myeloid dendritic cell cytokine production.

label: hypothesis textual entity
Defs: A textual entity that expresses an assertion that is intended to be tested.

label: anatomical junction
Defs: An anatomical structure that connects two structures.

label: positive regulation of leukocyte activation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of leukocyte activation.

label: cervical sclerite
Defs: The sclerite that is surrounded by the neck membrane.

label: esophagus secretion
Defs: A secretion that is part of a esophagus [Automatically generated definition].

label: accessory nerve maturation

label: negative regulation of T cell migration

label: intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron
Defs: A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to structures of telencephalic origins.

label: fat cell apoptotic process
Defs: Any apoptotic process in a fat cell.

label: regulation of cellular amide metabolic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving amides.

label: process quality
Defs: A quality which inheres in an process.

label: foregut epithelium

label: stipito-palpal muscle
Defs: The insect cranio-maxillar muscle that is attached to the stipes and the maxillary palpus.

label: negative regulation of adaptive immune response based on somatic recombination of immune receptors built from immunoglobulin superfamily domains
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of an adaptive immune response based on somatic recombination of immune receptors built from immunoglobulin superfamily domains. An example of this process is found in the Gnathostomata.

Defs: An s-block molecular entity is a molecular entity containing one or more atoms of an s-block element.

label: generalized
Defs: Affecting all regions without specificity of distribution.

label: sensory perception of taste
Defs: The series of events required for an organism to receive a gustatory stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Gustation involves the direct detection of chemical composition, usually through contact with chemoreceptor cells. This is a neurological process.

label: lipid biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids, compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent.

label: protein localization to membrane
Defs: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location in a membrane.

label: oligopotent
Defs: A cellular potency that is the capacity to form multiple differentiated cell types of a specific lineage and lack self renewing capacity.

label: pleura
Defs: The invaginated serous membrane that surrounds the lungs (the visceral portion) and lines the walls of the pleural cavity (parietal portion).

label: cardiac fibroblast cell development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a cardiac fibroblast over time, from its formation to the mature state. A cardiac fibroblast is a connective tissue cell of the heart which secretes an extracellular matrix rich in collagen and other macromolecules.

label: ribonucleoprotein complex disassembly
Defs: The disaggregation of a protein-RNA complex into its constituent components.

label: regulation of macrophage activation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency or rate of macrophage activation.

label: hindbrain morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structure of the hindbrain is generated and organized. The hindbrain is the region consisting of the medulla, pons and cerebellum. Areas of the hindbrain control motor and autonomic functions.

label: postgena
Defs: The posterior region of the head capsule that is continuous with the posterior region of the gena and is anterior to the postoccipital ridge.

label: anion homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of anions within an organism or cell.

label: positive regulation of peptide hormone secretion
Defs: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the regulated release of a peptide hormone from secretory granules.

label: regulation of monocyte chemotaxis

lateral region

Defs: A convex 3-D shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s exhibiting a by virtue of the bearer\'s exhibiting a consistently sized and approximately round cross-section along its length, which is many times larger than its diameter.

label: glutamate metabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glutamate, the anion of 2-aminopentanedioic acid.

label: regulation of postsynaptic membrane potential
Defs: Any process that modulates the potential difference across a post-synaptic membrane.

label: neurotransmitter receptor activity involved in regulation of postsynaptic membrane potential
Defs: Neurotransmitter receptor activity occurring in the postsynaptic membrane that is involved in regulating postsynaptic membrane potential, either directly (ionotropic receptors) or indirectly (e.g. via GPCR activation of an ion channel).

label: anatomical plane
Defs: A flat 2D plane intersecting an anatomical continuant, dividing it into two adjacent portions.

label: epithelium of foregut-midgut junction
Defs: An epithelium that is part of a foregut-midgut junction.

label: regulation of motor neuron migration
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of motor neuron migration.

label: cranial placode
Defs: Ectodermal placode that develops in the head into a part of the sensory nervous system. With a few exceptions (lens, adenohypophyseal), cranial placodes are neurogenic.

label: positive regulation of striated muscle contraction
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of striated muscle contraction.

label: serration
Defs: A surface feature shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having or lacking sharp straight-edged teeth pointing to the apex.

label: normal age

label: regulation of hematopoietic stem cell proliferation

label: bilateral symmetry

label: negative regulation of Schwann cell migration

label: CD14 molecule
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human CD14 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: saturated orange
Defs: A color consisting of orange hue and high saturation.

label: neural plate morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the neural plate are generated and organized. The neural plate is a specialized region of columnar epithelial cells in the dorsal ectoderm that will give rise to nervous system tissue.

label: lung growth
Defs: The increase in size or mass of a lung. In all air-breathing vertebrates the lungs are developed from the ventral wall of the oesophagus as a pouch which divides into two sacs. In amphibians and many reptiles the lungs retain very nearly this primitive sac-like character, but in the higher forms the connection with the esophagus becomes elongated into the windpipe and the inner walls of the sacs become more and more divided, until, in the mammals, the air spaces become minutely divided into tubes ending in small air cells, in the walls of which the blood circulates in a fine network of capillaries. In mammals the lungs are more or less divided into lobes, and each lung occupies a separate cavity in the thorax.

label: pectoral appendage apical ectodermal ridge
Defs: An apical ectodermal ridge that is part of a pectoral appendage bud.

label: nuclear lumen

label: negative regulation of bile acid secretion

Defs: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer includes all its components.

label: apical ectodermal ridge formation
Defs: The process that gives rise to the apical ectodermal ridge. This process pertains to the initial formation of a structure from unspecified parts.

label: placoid sensillum
Defs: The multiporous plate that is elongated.

label: phosphorus oxoacid
Defs: A pnictogen oxoacid which contains phosphorus and oxygen, at least one hydrogen atom bound to oxygen, and forms an ion by the loss of one or more protons.

label: positive regulation of neural crest cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of neural crest cell differentiation.

label: development of primary female sexual characteristics
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the primary female sexual characteristics over time, from their formation to the mature structure. The primary female sexual characteristics are the ovaries, and they develop in response to sex hormone secretion.

label: postsynaptic cytoskeleton organization
Defs: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising cytoskeletal filaments and their associated proteins in the postsynaptic cytoskeleton.

label: neutrophil homeostasis
Defs: The process of regulating the proliferation and elimination of neutrophils such that the total number of neutrophils within a whole or part of an organism is stable over time in the absence of an outside stimulus.

label: positive regulation of translation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA or circRNA.

label: cell morphogenesis
Defs: The developmental process in which the size or shape of a cell is generated and organized.

label: oviduct
Defs: The region of cuticle that is continuous with the genital chamber.

label: regulation of response to stimulus
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a response to a stimulus. Response to stimulus is a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus.

label: pleuroperitoneal canal lumen

label: aplastic

label: increased pigmentation

label: increased elevation relative to

label: polysaccharide binding

label: pathogenicity

label: arterial system smooth muscle

label: trigeminal nerve

label: columnar

label: negative regulation of sister chromatid segregation

label: arterial blood vessel

label: protein localization to actin cytoskeleton

label: T-cell surface glycoprotein CD5 (mouse)
Defs: A T-cell surface glycoprotein CD5 that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: iris

label: antimicrobial peptide secretion
Defs: The regulated release of an antimicrobial peptide from a cell or a tissue. Such peptides may have protective properties against bacteria, fungi, viruses, or protozoa.

label: dilated
Defs: A size quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being made wider or larger in all dimensions.

label: serotonin receptor activity
Defs: Combining with the biogenic amine serotonin and transmitting a signal across a membrane by activating some effector activity. Serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine) is a neurotransmitter and hormone found in vertebrates and invertebrates.

label: bile acid metabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving bile acids, a group of steroid carboxylic acids occurring in bile, where they are present as the sodium salts of their amides with glycine or taurine.

label: episternum
Defs: The sclerite of the insect thorax that is part of the pleuron and anterior to the pleural ridge and attached to the anterior margin of the epimeron.

label: cystic duct
Defs: The tubular structure that conducts gall bladder contents from the gall bladder to the common bile duct.

label: edible
Defs: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being suitable for use as food.

label: ethical approval textual entity
Defs: A textual entity that documents the ethical approval of some study design.

label: regulation of primary metabolic process

label: regulation of striated muscle contraction
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of striated muscle contraction.

label: SA node cell action potential

label: regulation of cellular macromolecule biosynthetic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cellular macromolecule biosynthetic process.

label: regulation of metabolic process

label: positive regulation of cell migration
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration.

label: normal tonicity
Defs: A tonicity which is relatively normal or average

label: duodenal papilla
Defs: One of the two small elevations on the mucosa of the duodenum, the major at the entrance of the conjoined pancreatic and common bile ducts and the minor at the entrance of the accessory pancreatic duct.

label: metasterno-metacoxal conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva of the mesothorax that joins the metasternum and the metacoxa.

label: positive regulation of protein catabolic process in the vacuole
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein catabolic process in the vacuole.

Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving organic acids, any acidic compound containing carbon in covalent linkage.

Defs: Outermost layer of cells surrounding the embryo.

label: Kit and Sca1-positive hematopoietic stem cell
Defs: A hematopoietic stem cell that has plasma membrane part Kit-positive, SCA-1-positive, CD150-positive and CD34-negative.

label: positive regulation of hematopoietic stem cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of hematopoietic stem cell proliferation.

label: response to toxic substance
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a toxic stimulus.

label: discrimination
Defs: A behavioral quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer\'s disposition to perceive differences between two or more stimuli.

label: oligodendrocyte progenitor proliferation
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of oligodendrocyte progenitor cells by cell division, resulting in the expansion of their population. Oligodendrocyte progenitors give rise to oligodendrocytes, which form the insulating myelin sheath of axons in the central nervous system.

label: positive regulation of mitotic nuclear division
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mitosis.

label: abdominal segment connective tissue
Defs: A portion of connective tissue that is part of an abdominal segment of trunk [Automatically generated definition].

label: eye primordium
Defs: Portion of tissue that is part of the anterior neural keel and will form the optic vesicle[ZFA]. A paired ectodermal placode that becomes invaginated to form the embryonic lens vesicles.

label: decreased fecundity
Defs: A fecundity which is relatively low.

label: objective specification

Defs: A publication that is about an investigation

label: negative regulation of skeletal muscle tissue growth
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle growth.

label: Golgi to transport vesicle transport
Defs: The directed movement of proteins from the Golgi to a transport vesicle. Continuously secreted proteins are sorted into transport vesicles that fuse with the plasma membrane, releasing their contents by exocytosis.

label: metanoto-metapleural conjunctiva
Defs: The noto-pleural conjunctiva that joins the metanotum and the metapleuron.

label: well differentiated
Defs: A cellular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of its having most of the cellular characteristics of the tissue of origin.

label: chorionic plate
Defs: That portion of the chorionic wall in the region of its uterine attachment, which gives rise to chorionic villi; it consists of the mesoderm that lines the chorionic vesicle and, on the maternal side, of the trophoblast that lines the intervillous spaces; in the last half of gestation, the mesodermal connective tissue is largely replaced by fibrinoid material, and the amnionic membrane is adherent to the fetal side of the plate.

label: tissue
Defs: Multicellular anatomical structure that consists of many cells of one or a few types, arranged in an extracellular matrix such that their long-range organisation is at least partly a repetition of their short-range organisation.

label: sodium salt
Defs: Any alkali metal salt having sodium(1+) as the cation.

label: postalar bridge
Defs: The region of cuticle of the dorso-lateral region of the pterothorax that is surrounded by the noto-pleural conjunctiva and articulated with the epimeron.

label: right hepatic artery
Defs: A hepatic artery that is part of a right lobe of liver.

label: microtubule polymerization or depolymerization
Defs: Assembly or disassembly of microtubules by the addition or removal of tubulin heterodimers from a microtubule.

label: positive regulation of chemotaxis
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a motile cell or organism in response to a specific chemical concentration gradient.

label: regulation of protein localization to presynapse
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to presynapse.

label: vascular associated smooth muscle cell development
Defs: The process aimed at the progression of a vascular smooth muscle cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell. A vascular smooth muscle cell is a non-striated, elongated, spindle-shaped cell found lining the blood vessels.

label: regulation of animal organ formation

The process begins with the specific processes that contribute to the appearance of the discrete structure, such as inductive events, and ends when the structural rudiment of the organ is recognizable, such as a condensation of mesenchymal cells into the organ rudiment.

label: positive regulation of mesenchymal cell proliferation
Defs: The process of activating or increasing the rate or extent of mesenchymal cell proliferation. Mesenchymal cells are loosely organized embryonic cells.

label: inferomedial tentorio-mandibular muscle
Defs: The cranio-mandibular muscle that extends between the anterior tentorial arm and the dorso-medial region of the insect mandible.

label: cellular cation homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of cations at the level of a cell.

label: regulation of carbohydrate biosynthetic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of carbohydrates.

label: variant shape
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue the bearer\'s having or exhibiting variation its shape.

label: lymphocyte apoptotic process
Defs: Any apoptotic process in a lymphocyte, a leukocyte commonly found in the blood and lymph that has the characteristics of a large nucleus, a neutral staining cytoplasm, and prominent heterochromatin.

label: positive regulation of type B pancreatic cell apoptotic process
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of type B pancreatic cell apoptotic process.

label: bone collagen fibril
Defs: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of bone tissue that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity.

label: protein localization to cilium
Defs: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within a cilium.

label: skin of lip
Defs: A zone of skin that is part of a lip [Automatically generated definition].

label: heart vasculature
Defs: An interconnected tubular multi-tissue structure that contains fluid that is actively transported around the heart.

label: trophectodermal cell differentiation
Defs: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a trophectoderm cell.

label: nucleon
Defs: Heavy nuclear particle: proton or neutron.

label: serous acinus
Defs: The secretory unit of a serous gland. The acinar portion is composed of serous secreting cells.

label: right horn of sinus venosus development
Defs: The progression of the right horn of the sinus venosus from its formation to the mature structure.

label: decreased radioactivity
Defs: A radioactivity which is relatively high.

label: cloaca
Defs: Common chamber into which the intestines and excretory system opens. Arises during development in all vertebrates, but in many it becomes subdivided, lost or incorporated into other structures.

label: nucleic acid transport
Defs: The directed movement of nucleic acids, single or double-stranded polynucleotides involved in the storage, transmission and transfer of genetic information, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: negative regulation of animal organ morphogenesis
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of animal organ morphogenesis.

label: vascular endothelial cell proliferation
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of blood vessel endothelial cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

label: receptor-type tyrosine-protein phosphatase C (mouse)
Defs: A receptor-type tyrosine-protein phosphatase C that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: peritoneal sac
Defs: A serous sac that is the aggregate of the peritoneum and the peritoneal cavity, located in the abdominal cavity.

label: neurotransmitter catabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of any of a group of substances that are released on excitation from the axon terminal of a presynaptic neuron of the central or peripheral nervous system and travel across the synaptic cleft to either excite or inhibit the target cell.

label: bifurcated
Defs: A branched quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being divided into two branches.

label: bladder organ
Defs: A membranous sac in animals that serves as the receptacle of a liquid or contains gas.

label: negative regulation of neuronal action potential
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of neuronal action potential.

label: positive regulation of cytokine production involved in immune response
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of cytokine production that contributes to an immune response.

label: distensible
Defs: A structure quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being capable of swelling or stretching.

label: cartesian spatial coordinate datum
Defs: A cartesian spatial coordinate datum is a representation of a point in a spatial region, in which equal changes in the magnitude of a coordinate value denote length qualities with the same magnitude

label: neuronal stem cell
Defs: Neural stem cell is characterized as an undifferentiated cell that originates from the neuroectoderm and has the capacity both to perpetually self-renew without differentiating and to generate multiple types of lineage-restricted progenitors.

label: abdominal ganglion
Defs: A ganglion that is part of a abdominal segment of trunk.

label: epithelium of rectum
Defs: An epithelium that is part of a rectum [Automatically generated definition].

label: tunica adventitia of blood vessel
Defs: The outermost layer of a blood vessel, composed mainly of fibrous tissue.

label: regulation of stem cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of stem cell differentiation.

label: optic vesicle formation
Defs: The developmental process pertaining to the initial formation of the optic vesicle from the lateral wall of the forebrain. This process begins with the specific processes that contribute to the appearance of the vesicle and ends when the vesicle has evaginated. The optic vesicle is the evagination of neurectoderm that precedes formation of the optic cup.

label: regulation of protein catabolic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by the destruction of the native, active configuration, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

label: positive regulation of cell growth involved in cardiac muscle cell development
Defs: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the growth of a cardiac muscle cell, where growth contributes to the progression of the cell over time from its initial formation to its mature state.

label: obsolete insomnia
Defs: A sleep pattern quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s inability to sleep.

label: splayed dorsal
Defs: A curvature quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being curved outwards from the back or upper surface of an organism.

label: moderate intensity
Defs: An intensity which is less than extreme in type or degree or effect or force.

label: dopamine binding
Defs: Binding to dopamine, a catecholamine neurotransmitter formed by aromatic-L-amino-acid decarboxylase from 3,4-dihydroxy-L-phenylalanine.

label: protarso-propretarsal conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva that encircles the propretarsus by joining the distal margin of the distalmost protarsomere and the proximal margin of the propretarsus.

label: forebrain development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the forebrain over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The forebrain is the anterior of the three primary divisions of the developing chordate brain or the corresponding part of the adult brain (in vertebrates, includes especially the cerebral hemispheres, the thalamus, and the hypothalamus and especially in higher vertebrates is the main control center for sensory and associative information processing, visceral functions, and voluntary motor functions).

label: pulmonary artery
Defs: An artery that carries deoxygenated blood from heart to the lungs. They are the only arteries (other than umbilical arteries in the fetus) that carry deoxygenated blood..

label: leukosialin
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human SPN gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: trophectoderm
Defs: Outermost layer of cells in the blastodermic vesicle, which will develop into the trophoblast layer and then contact the endometrium and take part in establishing the embryo\'s means of nutrition.

label: light green
Defs: A color consisting of green hue and high brightness.

label: insect leg muscle
Defs: The somatic muscle that is part of the insect leg.

label: circle of Willis
Defs: A circle of arteries that supply blood to the brain. The Circle of Willis comprises the following arteries: Anterior cerebral artery (left and right); Anterior communicating artery; Internal carotid artery (left and right); Posterior cerebral artery (left and right); Posterior communicating artery (left and right).The basilar artery and middle cerebral arteries, supplying the brain, are also considered part of the circle.

label: regulation of tetrapyrrole catabolic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of tetrapyrrole catabolic process.

label: regulation of type B pancreatic cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of type B pancreatic cell proliferation.

label: acetate transmembrane transporter activity
Defs: Enables the transfer of acetate from one side of a membrane to the other. Acetate is the 2-carbon carboxylic acid ethanoic acid.

label: curation subset ontology module
Defs: A subset ontology that is intended as a whitelist for curators using the ontology. Such a subset will exclude classes that curators should not use for curation.

label: neonatal
Defs: A maturity quality inhering to a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being at the point or short after birth.

label: trochantin
Defs: The sclerite that is located on the ventro-lateral region of the insect thorax and is attached to a coxa.

label: positive regulation of sodium ion transport
Defs: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of sodium ions (Na+) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: glycosaminoglycan
Defs: Any polysaccharide containing a substantial proportion of aminomonosaccharide residues.

label: Escherichia coli metabolite
Defs: Any bacterial metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Escherichia coli.

label: sex-specific
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being present in one sex and absent from the other in members of the same species.

label: visceral pleura
Defs: The inner serous membrane of the pulmonary pleural. The visceral pleura lines the lungs.

label: intestinal enteroendocrine cell
Defs: The various hormone- or neurotransmitter-secreting cells present throughout the mucosa of the intestinal tract.

label: increased female fertility
Defs: A female fertility which is relatively high.

label: negative regulation of microtubule binding
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of microtubule binding.

label: regulation of basement membrane organization
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly, disassembly or arrangement of constituent parts of the basement membrane.

label: pancreatic ductal cell
Defs: Epithelial cell found in the ducts of the pancreas. This cell type contributes to the high luminal pH.

label: optic vesicle
Defs: The optic vesicle is the evagination of neurectoderm that precedes formation of the optic cup[GO]. Portion of tissue that is comprised of neuroepitheium which has pinched off from the anterior neural keel and will form the optic cup[ZFA].

label: negative regulation of osteoclast proliferation
Defs: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of the multiplication or reproduction of osteoclasts, resulting in the expansion of an osteoclast cell population.

label: bronchial epithelial cell
Defs: An epithelial cell of the bronchus.

label: negative regulation of megakaryocyte differentiation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of megakaryocyte differentiation.

label: organic substance metabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving an organic substance, any molecular entity containing carbon.

label: lysosome
Defs: A small lytic vacuole that has cell cycle-independent morphology found in most animal cells and that contains a variety of hydrolases, most of which have their maximal activities in the pH range 5-6. The contained enzymes display latency if properly isolated. About 40 different lysosomal hydrolases are known and lysosomes have a great variety of morphologies and functions.

label: negative regulation of euchromatin binding
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of euchromatin binding.

label: lung epithelium
Defs: The epithelial layer of the lung.

label: regulation of meiotic cell cycle process involved in oocyte maturation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of meiotic cell cycle process involved in oocyte maturation.

label: heterocycle catabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of heterocyclic compounds, those with a cyclic molecular structure and at least two different atoms in the ring (or rings).

label: tube lumen
Defs: A hole in a tube[GO].

label: embryo stage
Defs: A life cycle stage that starts with fertilization and ends with the fully formed embryo.

label: temporal distribution quality
Defs: A temporal distribution pattern of process occurrences within a regulation/reference process.

label: frontoclypeal ridge
Defs: The ridge of the head capsule that separates the clypeus and the frons.

label: neuromuscular junction of skeletal muscle fiber
Defs: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a skeletal muscle fiber.

label: primary heart field
Defs: A specific region of the lateral mesoderm that will form the primary beating heart tube. In mammals the primary heart field gives rise to the left ventricle.

label: serrated
Defs: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of having sharp straight-edged teeth pointing to the apex.

label: cervical artery
Defs: An artery of the neck.

label: duration of disease
Defs: A duration quality of a process inhering in a disease by virtue of the bearer\'s duration of an impairment of health or of a condition of abnormal functioning.

label: gamete
Defs: A mature sexual reproductive cell having a single set of unpaired chromosomes.

label: mesenchyme derived from neural crest
Defs: Mesenchyme that develops_from the neural crest[Automatically generated definition].

label: regulation of glial cell apoptotic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of glial cell apoptotic process.

label: sinusoid
Defs: Small blood vessel similar to a capillary but with a fenestrated endothelium. Sinusoids are found in the liver, lymphoid tissue, endocrine organs, and hematopoietic organs such as the bone marrow and the spleen. Sinusoids found within terminal villi of the placenta are not comparable to these; they possess a continuous endothelium and complete basal lamina[WP].

label: skeletal system development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the skeleton over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The skeleton is the bony framework of the body in vertebrates (endoskeleton) or the hard outer envelope of insects (exoskeleton or dermoskeleton).

label: mucosa of right uterine tube
Defs: A mucosa that is part of a right uterine tube [Automatically generated definition].

label: lamina propria of esophagus
Defs: A lamina propria that is part of a esophagus [Automatically generated definition].

label: obsolete electromagnetic (EM) radiation quality
Defs: OBSOLETE A radiation quality that inheres in a bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with electromagnetic radiation.

label: hepatic immune response
Defs: An immune response taking place in the liver.

label: negative regulation of pigment cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of pigment cell differentiation.

label: protein-containing complex assembly
Defs: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of macromolecules to form a protein-containing complex.

label: degree of pigmentation
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having or lacking of substances produced by living organisms that have a color resulting from selective color absorption.

label: negative regulation of glycogen catabolic process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glycogen.

label: bitufted cell morphology
Defs: A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have two clusters of primary dendrites that originate directly and extend from opposite ends of the soma, and axons that form a plexus which spreads widely. Compared to the narrow vertical axonal projection of bipolar morphology, and the \'horse-tail\' axonal cluster of double boquet cells, bitufted morphology has wide horizontal axonal spans, and branching that occur close to the soma. Their vertical projection is also less extensive and crosses mostly to neighboring layers.

label: prominin-1 (mouse)
Defs: A prominin-1 that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: associated mesenchyme of foregut-midgut junction
Defs: Mesenchyme that is part of a foregut-midgut junction.

label: vagus nerve
Defs: Cranial nerve that branches into the lateral (to body sense organs) and the intestino-accessorial (to the skin, muscles of shoulder, hyoid, larynx, gut, lungs, and heart).

label: abnormal cell
Defs: A cell found in an organism or derived from an organism exhibiting a phenotype that deviates from the expected phenotype of any native cell type of that organism. Abnormal cells are typically found in disease states or disease models.

label: everted
Defs: An oriented quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being turned outward in placement.

label: case report section
Defs: A part of a document about the medical history of a specific patient as it relates to the topic of the document.

label: embryonic head
Defs: A head that is part of a embryo.

label: increased speed
Defs: A speed which is relatively high.

label: corneal stroma collagen fibril
Defs: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of corneal stroma that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity.

label: embryonic placenta development
Defs: The embryonically driven process whose specific outcome is the progression of the placenta over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The placenta is an organ of metabolic interchange between fetus and mother, partly of embryonic origin and partly of maternal origin.

label: secretory granule localization
Defs: Any process in which a secretory granule is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within the cell.

label: prophragma-mesophragmal muscle
Defs: The dorsal longitudinal thoracic muscle that extends between the medial region of the prophragma and the medial region of the mesophragma.

label: ovary stroma
Defs: The stroma of the ovary is a peculiar soft tissue, abundantly supplied with blood vessels, consisting for the most part of spindle-shaped cells with a small amount of ordinary connective tissue. These cells have been regarded by some anatomists as unstriped muscle cells, which, indeed, they most resemble; by others as connective-tissue cells. On the surface of the organ this tissue is much condensed, and forms a layer composed of short connective-tissue fibers, with fusiform cells between them. The stroma of the ovary may contain interstitial cells resembling those of the testis.

label: mobility
Defs: A quality of inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s disposition to move freely.

label: lymphocyte antigen 76 (mouse)
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the Ly76 gene in mouse.

label: shortened
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s length being notably lower than its width.

label: nuclear chromosome segregation
Defs: The process in which genetic material, in the form of nuclear chromosomes, is organized into specific structures and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets. Nuclear chromosome segregation begins with the condensation of chromosomes, includes chromosome separation, and ends when chromosomes have completed movement to the spindle poles.

label: microcirculatory vessel
Defs: A vessel of the microcirculature, lying between the arterioles and venules; includes capillaries (blood and lymphatic), metarterioles and arteriovenous anastomoses.

label: cartilaginous condensation
Defs: Cell condensation that is an aggregation of mesenchymal cells that are committed to differentiate into chondroblasts and chondrocytes.

label: elytral stria
Defs: The groove on an elytron that is longitidinal (parallel to the anterior-posterior axis).

label: pectoral girdle skeleton
Defs: A subdivision of a limb or fin skeleton consisting of bones which connects the upper limb or fin to the axial skeleton on each side. It consists of the clavicle and scapula in humans and, in those species with three bones in the pectoral girdle, the coracoid. Some mammalian species (e.g. the dog and the horse) have only the scapula. In humans, the only joints between the shoulder girdle and axial skeleton are the sternoclavicular joints on each side. No joint exists between each scapula and the rib cage; instead the muscular connection between the two permits relatively great mobility of the shoulder girdle in relation to the pelvic girdle. In those species having only the scapula, no joint exists between the forelimb and the thorax, the only attachment being muscular[WP]. Examples: There are only two instances, right and left pectoral girdle skeletons.

label: positive regulation of cell proliferation involved in heart morphogenesis
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell proliferation involved in heart morphogenesis.

label: costa
Defs: The insect wing vein of the costal field that is anterior to the subcosta.

label: chromosome condensation
Defs: The progressive compaction of dispersed interphase chromatin into threadlike chromosomes prior to mitotic or meiotic nuclear division, or during apoptosis, in eukaryotic cells.

label: organic hydroxy compound biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of organic hydroxy compound.

label: eosinophilic
Defs: An affinity inhering in an anatomical structure by virtue of the bearer exhibiting a molecular interaction for eosin dye.

label: cyclic compound
Defs: Any molecule that consists of a series of atoms joined together to form a ring.

label: negative regulation of epithelial to mesenchymal transition
Defs: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of epithelial to mesenchymal transition. Epithelial to mesenchymal transition where an epithelial cell loses apical/basolateral polarity, severs intercellular adhesive junctions, degrades basement membrane components and becomes a migratory mesenchymal cell.

label: macrophage antigen processing and presentation
Defs: The process in which a macrophage expresses antigen (peptide or lipid) on its cell surface in association with an MHC protein complex.

label: positive regulation of respiratory gaseous exchange
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of respiratory gaseous exchange.

label: external integument structure
Defs: Structures of the dermis, epidermis, glands and pigment cells recognizable on the external surfaces of the integument.

label: muscle organ development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the muscle over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The muscle is an organ consisting of a tissue made up of various elongated cells that are specialized to contract and thus to produce movement and mechanical work.

label: episodic
Defs: An occurrence quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having a course that occurs occasionally.

label: regulation of peptidyl-tyrosine phosphorylation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the phosphorylation of peptidyl-tyrosine.

label: gland
Defs: An organ that functions as a secretory or excretory organ.

label: cell proliferation in midbrain
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population in the midbrain.

label: reproductive quality
Defs: An organismal quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s ability to produce new life or offspring.

label: endocardial cushion development
Defs: The progression of a cardiac cushion over time, from its initial formation to the mature structure. The endocardial cushion is a specialized region of mesenchymal cells that will give rise to the heart septa and valves.

label: fibrinogen complex
Defs: A highly soluble, elongated protein complex found in blood plasma and involved in clot formation. It is converted into fibrin monomer by the action of thrombin.
