In the mouse, fibrinogen is a hexamer, 46 nm long and 9 nm maximal diameter, containing two sets of nonidentical chains (alpha, beta, and gamma) linked together by disulfide bonds.

label: enteric smooth muscle cell
Defs: A smooth muscle cell of the intestine.

label: dorsal longitudinal thoracic muscle
Defs: The insect thoracic muscle that is not fan-shaped and runs along the dorsal region, parallel to the anterior-posterior axis.

label: normal tendency
Defs: A tendency which is relatively normal or average

label: positive regulation of macromolecule metabolic process
Defs: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving macromolecules, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass.

label: increased concentration
Defs: A concentration which is higher relative to the normal or average.

label: negative regulation of axonogenesis
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of axonogenesis.

label: compatible
Defs: A compatibility quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being capable of harmonious coexistence.

label: chromosome organization involved in meiotic cell cycle
Defs: A process of chromosome organization that is involved in a meiotic cell cycle.

label: positive regulation of protein-containing complex assembly
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein complex assembly.

label: monoamine transport
Defs: The directed movement of monoamines, organic compounds that contain one amino group that is connected to an aromatic ring by an ethylene group (-CH2-CH2-), into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: white matter of medulla oblongata
Defs: A white matter that is part of a medulla oblongata.

label: presumptive endocardium
Defs: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a endocardium.

label: regulation of pancreatic A cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of pancreatic A cell differentiation.

label: phenol-containing compound catabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a phenol, any compound containing one or more hydroxyl groups directly attached to an aromatic carbon ring.

label: axial mesoderm
Defs: The axial mesoderm includes the prechordal mesoderm and the chordamesoderm. It gives rise to the prechordal plate and to the notochord.

label: positive regulation of neural precursor cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of neural precursor cell proliferation.

label: respiratory tube
Defs: A tube in the respiratory system. Examples: bronchus, bronchiole, trachea.

label: generation of precursor metabolites and energy
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of precursor metabolites, substances from which energy is derived, and any process involved in the liberation of energy from these substances.

label: premature
Defs: A quality of a process which starts earlier than the natural start time or the reference process.

label: cellular process involved in reproduction in multicellular organism
Defs: A process, occurring at the cellular level, that is involved in the reproductive function of a multicellular organism.

label: tight
Defs: A pattern quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being compact or dense in arrangement.

label: export from cell
Defs: The directed movement of some substance from a cell, into the extracellular region. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via exocytosis.

label: deep region
Defs: Anatomical region located deep within an organism or structure.

label: ion homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of ions within an organism or cell.

label: keratinous
Defs: A composition quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s consisting of keratin.

label: mononuclear cell differentiation
Defs: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a mononuclear cell.

label: regulation of cation transmembrane transport
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cation transmembrane transport.

label: cutaneous elastic tissue
Defs: The slender connective tissue fiber in the extracellular matrix of skin tissue that is composed of microfibrils and amorphous elastin and is characterized by great elasticity.

label: carboxylic acid transmembrane transporter activity
Defs: Enables the transfer of carboxylic acids from one side of a membrane to the other. Carboxylic acids are organic acids containing one or more carboxyl (COOH) groups or anions (COO-).

label: gular ridge
Defs: Each ridge on the ventral region of the head capsule marking the sides of the gula.

label: negative regulation of endothelial cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of endothelial cell differentiation.

label: genotypic sex
Defs: A biological sex quality inhering in an individual based upon genotypic composition of sex chromosomes.

label: laryngeal apparatus
Defs: Apparatus located between the lungs and the buccal cavity. This apparatus is composed of a pair of arytenoid cartilages that are supported by the cricoid ring.

label: enzyme inhibitor
Defs: A compound or agent that combines with an enzyme in such a manner as to prevent the normal substrate-enzyme combination and the catalytic reaction.

label: Fc receptor complex
Defs: A protein complex composed of a subunit or subunits capable of binding the Fc portion of an immunoglobulin with additional signaling components. The complex functions as a receptor for immunoglobulin.

label: decreased fluorescence
Defs: A fluorescence which is lower than normal.

label: protein localization to secretory granule
Defs: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within a secretory granule.

label: laterotergite
Defs: The sclerite of the insect thorax or the insect abdomen that is on the lateral region of the notum.

label: retina development in camera-type eye
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the retina over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The retina is the innermost layer or coating at the back of the eyeball, which is sensitive to light and in which the optic nerve terminates.

label: epithelium of esophagus
Defs: The epithelial layer that lines the luminal space of the esophagus.

label: abdomen nerve
Defs: A nerve that is part of an abdomen [Automatically generated definition].

label: iris blood vessel
Defs: A blood vessel that is part of a iris [Automatically generated definition].

label: increased position
Defs: A position which is relatively high.

label: material entity
Defs: An independent continuant that is spatially extended whose identity is independent of that of other entities and can be maintained through time.

label: negative regulation of cardiac muscle cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle cell differentiation.

label: antimicrobial food preservative
Defs: A food preservative which prevents decomposition of food by preventing the growth of fungi or bacteria. In European countries, E-numbers for permitted food preservatives are from E200 to E299, divided into sorbates (E200-209), benzoates (E210-219), sulfites (E220-229), phenols and formates (E230-239), nitrates (E240-259), acetates (E260-269), lactates (E270-279), propionates (E280-289) and others (E290-299).

label: cuticle
Defs: Tough but flexible, non-mineral outer coverings of an organism, or parts of an organism, that provide protection. Cuticles are non-homologous, differing in their origin, structure and chemical composition[WP].

label: neural crest cell differentiation
Defs: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a neural crest cell.

label: parallelodromous
Defs: A branched quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having two or more parallel primary branches originate beside each other and converge apically.

label: chalcogen
Defs: Any p-block element belonging to the group 16 family of the periodic table.

label: positive regulation of extracellular matrix organization
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of extracellular matrix organization.

label: noradrenergic cell groups
Defs: Collections of neurons in the central nervous system that have been demonstrated by histochemical fluorescence to contain the neurotransmitter norepinephrine (noradrenalin).

label: near-projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron
Defs: A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects axons locally rather than distantly.

label: glial cell projection
Defs: A prolongation or process extending from a glial cell.

label: atrioventricular node cell development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an atrioventricular (AV) node cell over time, from its formation to the mature state.

label: negative regulation of dendritic spine morphogenesis
Defs: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of dendritic spine morphogenesis, the process in which the anatomical structures of a dendritic spine are generated and organized. A dendritic spine is a protrusion from a dendrite and a specialized subcellular compartment involved in synaptic transmission.

label: positive regulation of anion transmembrane transport
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of anion transmembrane transport.

label: left hepatic vein
Defs: A hepatic vein that is part of a left lobe of liver.

label: positive regulation of intracellular protein transport
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of proteins within cells.

label: cellular response to alkaloid
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an alkaloid stimulus. Alkaloids are a large group of nitrogenous substances found in naturally in plants, many of which have extracts that are pharmacologically active.

label: negative regulation of antimicrobial peptide production
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of antimicrobial peptide production.

label: conclusion section
Defs: A part of a document used to summarize the findings discussed in the document. The conclusion section is typically found near the end of a document.

label: regulation of cardiac muscle cell myoblast differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle cell myoblast differentiation.

label: embryonic structure
Defs: Anatomical structure that is part of an embryo.

label: molar mass
Defs: A physical quality that inheres in a homogeneous substance containing 6.02 x 1023 atoms or molecules.

label: inorganic anion transport
Defs: The directed movement of inorganic anions into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Inorganic anions are atoms or small molecules with a negative charge which do not contain carbon in covalent linkage.

label: lymphocyte activation involved in immune response
Defs: A change in morphology and behavior of a lymphocyte resulting from exposure to a specific antigen, mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or soluble factor, leading to the initiation or perpetuation of an immune response.

label: pharyngeal arch artery 1
Defs: The vessels formed within the first pair of branchial arches in embryogenesis.

label: skeletal muscle cell proliferation
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of skeletal muscle cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

label: enucleate erythrocyte
Defs: An erythrocyte lacking a nucleus.

label: negative regulation of glycogen biosynthetic process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycogen.

label: cardiac muscle hypertrophy
Defs: The enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of the heart muscle due to an increase in size of cardiac muscle cells without cell division.

label: quality of a solid
Defs: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s exhibiting the physical characteristics of an entity characterized by particles arranged such that their shape and volume are relatively stable.

label: intraciliary transport
Defs: The bidirectional movement of large protein complexes along microtubules within a cilium, mediated by motor proteins.

label: entire surface of organism
Defs: Anatomical surface, which is the external surface of the whole body. Examples: There is only one body surface.

label: vasculature of iris
Defs: A vasculature that is part of a iris [Automatically generated definition].

label: ciliary processes
Defs: The ciliary processes are formed by the inward folding of the various layers of the choroid, i.e. , the choroid proper and the lamina basalis, and are received between corresponding foldings of the suspensory ligament of the lens.

label: normal virulence
Defs: A virulence which is relatively normal or average

label: light cyan
Defs: A color consisting of cyan hue and high brightness.

label: direct ossification
Defs: The formation of bone or of a bony substance, or the conversion of fibrous tissue or of cartilage into bone or a bony substance, that does not require the replacement of preexisting tissues.

label: negative regulation of microvillus assembly
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of microvillus assembly.

label: establishment of cell polarity involved in ameboidal cell migration
Defs: The specification and formation of anisotropic intracellular organization that contributes to the self-propelled directed movement of an ameboid cell.

label: placental hematopoietic stem cell
Defs: A hematopoietic stem cell of the placenta. This cell type is first observed E10.5 This cell type may give rise to fetal liver hematopoietic stem cells.

label: integral component of Golgi membrane
Defs: The component of the Golgi membrane consisting of the gene products and protein complexes having at least some part of their peptide sequence embedded in the hydrophobic region of the membrane.

label: chitosome
Defs: An intracellular membrane-bounded particle found in fungi and containing chitin synthase; it synthesizes chitin microfibrils. Chitin synthase activity exists in chitosomes and they are proposed to act as a reservoir for regulated transport of chitin synthase enzymes to the division septum.

label: cholangiocyte proliferation
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of cholangiocytes, resulting in the expansion of the cholangiocyte population. A cholangiocyte is an epithelial cell that is part of the bile duct. Cholangiocytes contribute to bile secretion via net release of bicarbonate and water.

label: positive regulation of ribosome biogenesis
Defs: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of ribosome biogenesis. Ribosome biogenesis is the cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of ribosome subunits.

label: structure, cavities
Defs: A structural quality that inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s containing hollow areas.

label: unlumenized
Defs: A structure quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s lacking of a three dimensional space surrounded by one or more anatomical structures and containing one or more anatomical substances.

label: metapleuron
Defs: The region of the cuticle on the lateral region of the metathorax that is attached to the metanotum and the metasternum, and is attached to the metacoxa by the metacoxal muscle and the basal metacoxal conjunctiva.

label: caption
Defs: A textual entity that describes a figure

label: esophagus
Defs: Tube that connects the pharynx to the stomach. In mammals, the oesophagus connects the buccal cavity with the stomach. The stratified squamous non-keratinised epithelium lining the buccal cavity is continued through the pharynx down into the oesophagus. The lowest part of the oesophagus (ca. 2 cm) is lined with gastric mucosa and covered by peritoneum. The main body of the oesophagus is lined with small, simple mucous glands. Each gland opens into the lumen by a long duct which pierces the muscularis mucosae (Wilson and Washington, 1989). A sphincter is situated at the point where the oesophagus enters the stomach to prevent gastro-oesophageal reflux, i.e. to prevent acidic gastric contents from reaching stratified epithelia of the oesophagus, where they can cause inflammation and irritation (Wilson and Washington, 1989; Brown et al., 1993).

label: myeloperoxidase
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human MPO gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: negative regulation of response to biotic stimulus
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of a response to biotic stimulus.

label: regulation of smooth muscle cell chemotaxis
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of smooth muscle cell chemotaxis.

label: sensory system development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a sensory system over time from its formation to the mature structure.

label: regulation of actin filament-based process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of any cellular process that depends upon or alters the actin cytoskeleton.

label: decreased elasticity
Defs: An elasticity which is relatively low.

label: membrane
Defs: A lipid bilayer along with all the proteins and protein complexes embedded in it an attached to it.

label: midbrain neuromere
Defs: A neuromere that is part of the presumptive midbrain.

label: increased fragility
Defs: A fragility which is relatively high.

label: regulation of defense response to fungus
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of defense response to fungus.

label: carboxylic acid binding
Defs: Binding to a carboxylic acid, an organic acid containing one or more carboxyl (COOH) groups or anions (COO-).

label: monosaccharide
Defs: Parent monosaccharides are polyhydroxy aldehydes H[CH(OH)]nC(=O)H or polyhydroxy ketones H-[CHOH]n-C(=O)[CHOH]m-H with three or more carbon atoms. The generic term \'monosaccharide\' (as opposed to oligosaccharide or polysaccharide) denotes a single unit, without glycosidic connection to other such units. It includes aldoses, dialdoses, aldoketoses, ketoses and diketoses, as well as deoxy sugars, provided that the parent compound has a (potential) carbonyl group.

label: outflow tract septum morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the outflow tract septum are generated and organized. The outflow tract septum is a partition in the outflow tract.

label: somatic nervous system
Defs: Part of peripheral nervous system that includes the somatic parts of the cranial and spinal nerves and their ganglia and the peripheral sensory receptors.

label: cell proliferation involved in compound eye morphogenesis
Defs: The multiplication or reproduction of cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population that contributes to compound eye morphogenesis.

label: cardioblast
Defs: A stem cell that can give rise to multiple cell types (i.e. smooth muscle, endothelial) in the developing heart.

label: appendicular skeleton
Defs: Subdivision of skeleton which which consists of all the skeletal elements in in the pectoral and pelvic appendage complexes[cjm].

label: basket cell morphology
Defs: A cell morphology that inheres in multipolar neurons with densely branched terminal axonal arborizations that form basket-like structures surrounding and synapsing to the somas of target cells.

label: phosphorylated
Defs: A quality inhering in a protein or a molecule by virtue of the bearer\'s having a phosphate (PO4) group.

label: oocyte localization involved in germarium-derived egg chamber formation
Defs: Directed movement of the oocyte, following its specification, from its original central position in the cyst to a posterior position relative to the nurse cells of the egg chamber, and its maintenance in this posterior location. This is the first sign of anterior-posterior asymmetry in the developing egg chamber.

label: amniotic fold
Defs: A sheet of somatopleure that grows upward over the embryo and eventually meets in the midline enclosing the embryo, eventually giving rise to the amnion and chorion[Kardong].

label: positive regulation of monocyte antigen processing and presentation
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of monocyte antigen processing and presentation.

label: regulation of syncytium formation by plasma membrane fusion
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a syncytium, a mass of cytoplasm containing several nuclei enclosed within a single plasma membrane, by the fusion of the plasma membranes of two or more individual cells.

label: arrested
Defs: A quality of a process which ends earlier than the natural end time or reference process.

label: cell-cell signaling involved in cell fate commitment
Defs: Signaling at long or short range between cells that results in the commitment of a cell to a certain fate.

label: necessity (continuant)
Defs: A quality of a single physical entity inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer is essential or indispensable.

label: regulation of signaling
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a signaling process.

label: increased variability of rate
Defs: A variability of rate which is relatively high.

label: trans-synaptic signaling by lipid, modulating synaptic transmission
Defs: Cell-cell signaling between presynapse and postsynapse, via the release and reception of lipid molecules, that modulates the synaptic transmission properties of the synapse.

label: appendage girdle region
Defs: An organism subdivision that encompasses the region containing the pectoral or pelvic girdle. Note that this includes both the skeletal elements and associated tissues (integument, muscle, etc).

label: pancreatic duct
Defs: A duct that collects and carries secretions of the exocrine pancreas to the intestine.

label: regulation of meiotic cell cycle
Defs: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of progression through the meiotic cell cycle.

label: bacterial mating type
Defs: A mating type that indicates whether the F plasmid has integrated into the chromosome.

label: mesenchyme of lower jaw
Defs: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing lower jaw [Automatically generated definition].

label: abdominal sternite I-abdominal sternite II conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva of the insect abdomen that connects the abdominal sternite I and the abdominal sternite II.

label: absent
Defs: A quality denoting the lack of an entity.

label: negative regulation of mesenchymal cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of mesenchymal cell proliferation. A mesenchymal cell is a cell that normally gives rise to other cells that are organized as three-dimensional masses, rather than sheets.

label: lymphoid lineage cell migration
Defs: The orderly movement of a lymphoid lineage cell from one site to another. A lymphoid lineage cell, also called a lymphoid lineage restricted progenitor cell, is a progenitor cell restricted to the lymphoid lineage.

label: dark red brown
Defs: A color consisting of red and brown hue and low brightness.

label: polypyrrole
Defs: A compound composed of two or more pyrrole units.

label: oral mucosa squamous cell
Defs: Squamous cell of oral epithelium.

label: human metabolite
Defs: Any mammalian metabolite  produced during a metabolic reaction in humans (Homo sapiens).

label: normal circumference
Defs: A circumference which is relatively normal or average

label: positive regulation of branching morphogenesis of a nerve
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of branching morphogenesis of a nerve.

label: regulation of antigen processing and presentation of peptide or polysaccharide antigen via MHC class II
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of antigen processing and presentation of antigen (peptide or polysaccharide) via MHC class II.

label: hepatic portal system
Defs: A portal system that begins in capillaries in the wall of the digestive tract and and runs as the hepatic portal vein to the liver.

label: group
Defs: A defined linked collection of atoms or a single atom within a molecular entity.

label: peramorphic growth
Defs: A heterochronic growth quality inhering in an organism, structure, or group of organisms by virtue of the bearer\'s increased growth.

label: negative regulation of glucagon secretion
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of glucagon.

label: proliferative
Defs: A cellular quality inhering in a cell that arises by virtue of whether the bearer exhibits the ability to grow and proliferate in number through cell division.

label: positive regulation of phosphorus metabolic process
Defs: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving phosphorus or compounds containing phosphorus.

label: regulation of cardiac muscle tissue development
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle tissue development.

label: Golgi inheritance
Defs: The partitioning of Golgi apparatus between daughter cells at cell division.

label: regulation of humoral immune response
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of a humoral immune response.

label: lingual nerve
Defs: The lingual nerve is a branch of the mandibular nerve (CN V3), itself a branch of the trigeminal nerve, which supplies sensory innervation to the tongue. It also carries fibers from the facial nerve, which return taste information from the anterior two thirds of the tongue.

label: negative regulation of melanosome transport
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of melanosome transport.

label: neurocranium
Defs: Subdivision of skeletal system that surrounds and protects the brain. Includes the skull base, sensory capsules and the central part of the skull roof.

label: mesenchyme derived from trunk neural crest
Defs: Mesenchyme that develops_from a trunk neural crest.

label: non-membrane-bounded organelle assembly
Defs: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a non-membrane-bounded organelle.

label: rule
Defs: A rule is an executable which guides, defines, restricts actions.

label: cell cycle process
Defs: The cellular process that ensures successive accurate and complete genome replication and chromosome segregation.

label: surfactant secreting cell
Defs: A cell that specializes in secretion of surfactant in the alveoli of the lung.

label: cellular response to iron ion
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an iron ion stimulus.

label: lymphocyte antigen 6G
Defs: An Ly-6-like protein that is a translation product of the mouse Ly6g gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: interventricular septum endocardium
Defs: An endocardium that is part of a interventricular septum [Automatically generated definition].

label: glucan metabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glucans, polysaccharides consisting only of glucose residues.

label: negative regulation of defecation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of defecation.

label: gena
Defs: The lateral region of the head capsule, connected dorsally to the sides of the vertex.

label: located in
Defs: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s location within another entity.

label: brain microvascular endothelial cell
Defs: Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a brain.

label: positive regulation of smooth muscle tissue development
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle tissue development.

label: pericardial fat
Defs: The sum of epicardial and paracardial fat deposits.

label: enzyme activator complex
Defs: A protein complex capable of activating an enzyme. Activating subunits may dissociate from the catalytic unit before the enzyme is active.

label: regulation of stem cell division
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of stem cell division.

label: positive regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
Defs: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

label: monoploid
Defs: A ploidy quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s containing a single set of unique homologous chromosomes.

label: pelvic appendage bud mesenchyme
Defs: Mesenchyme that is part of a pelvic appendage bud.

label: regulation of immune effector process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of an immune effector process.

label: mesoderm morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structures of the mesoderm are generated and organized.

label: future diencephalon
Defs: The foremost region of the future forebrain that develops into the diencephalon.

label: accessory nerve morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structure of the accessory nerve is generated and organized. The spinal branch of this motor nerve innervates the trapezius and the sternocleidomastoid muscles. The cranial branch joins the vagus nerve and innervates the same targets as the vagus nerve.

label: terminal bronchiole
Defs: The last conducting structure of non-respiratory bronchioles; after this point, the airways have alveoli in their walls.

label: external soft tissue zone
Defs: A region or zone on the surface of an organism that encompasses skin and any adnexa, down through muscles and bounded by underlying skeletal support structures.

label: regulation of actomyosin structure organization
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures containing both actin and myosin or paramyosin.

label: cavity of left atrium
Defs: Luminal space of the left atrium of the heart.

label: inferior side
Defs: The side that is lower relative to the substrate.

label: plug shaped
Defs: A shape that is in the form of a plug, being tube-like and expanded on one end.

label: negative regulation of apoptotic process involved in outflow tract morphogenesis
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of apoptotic process involved in outflow tract morphogenesis.

label: carboxamide
Defs: An amide of a carboxylic acid, having the structure RC(=O)NR2. The term is used as a suffix in systematic name formation to denote the -C(=O)NH2 group including its carbon atom.

label: metal ion homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of metal ions within an organism or cell.

label: regulation of dendritic cell apoptotic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of dendritic cell apoptotic process.

label: decreased affinity
Defs: An affinity which is relatively low.

label: vacuole
Defs: A closed structure, found only in eukaryotic cells, that is completely surrounded by unit membrane and contains liquid material. Cells contain one or several vacuoles, that may have different functions from each other. Vacuoles have a diverse array of functions. They can act as a storage organelle for nutrients or waste products, as a degradative compartment, as a cost-effective way of increasing cell size, and as a homeostatic regulator controlling both turgor pressure and pH of the cytosol.

label: fungal metabolite
Defs: Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in fungi, the kingdom that includes microorganisms such as the yeasts and moulds.

label: pectoral girdle region
Defs: An organism subdivision that includes the pectoral girdle skeleton and associated soft tissue. Note that this includes both the skeletal elements and associated tissues (integument, muscle, etc). Examples: There are only two instances in an organism, right and left pectoral girdle regions.

label: negative regulation of vascular associated smooth muscle cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vascular smooth muscle cell proliferation.

label: pectoral appendage vasculature
Defs: A vasculature that is part of a pectoral appendage.

label: ciliated epithelial cell of esophagus
Defs: A ciliated epithelial cell of the esophagus.

label: positive regulation of AV node cell action potential
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of AV node cell action potential.

label: parasympathetic nerve
Defs: A nerve that is part of a parasympathetic nervous system [Automatically generated definition].

label: concentrated
Defs: A concentration quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s exhibiting concentration.

label: liquid configuration
Defs: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s parts having the arrangement which exhibits characteristics of liquids.

label: neuron projection membrane
Defs: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a neuron projection.

label: CD34-positive, CD38-positive granulocyte monocyte progenitor
Defs: A granulocyte monocyte progenitor is CD34-positive, CD38-positive, IL-3receptor-alpha-positive and is CD45RA-negative.

label: blood
Defs: A fluid that is composed of blood plasma and erythrocytes.

label: cranial neural crest
Defs: Neural crest cells (NCCs) originating in the anterior part of the developing embryo and residing between the mid-diencephalon and the forming hindbrain; cranial NCCs migrate dorsolaterally to form the craniofacial mesenchyme that differentiates into various craniofacial cartilages and bones, cranial neurons, glia, and connective tissues of the face; these cells enter the pharyngeal pouches and arches where they give rise to thymic cells, bones of the middle ear and jaw (mandible), and the odontoblasts of the tooth primordia; like their counterparts in the trunk, cranial NCCs also contribute to the developing peripheral nervous system, along with the pigmented cell (i.e. melanocyte) lineage.

label: regulation of endothelial cell activation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of endothelial cell activation.

label: myeloid cell activation involved in immune response
Defs: A change in the morphology or behavior of a myeloid cell resulting from exposure to an activating factor such as a cellular or soluble ligand, leading to the initiation or perpetuation of an immune response.

label: glycoprotein
Defs: A compound in which a carbohydrate component is covalently bound to a protein component.

label: negative regulation of mesoderm development
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of mesoderm development.

label: acidophilic cytoplasm
Defs: Cytoplasm that exhibits a characteristic staining and color, red or pink, with Eosin stain.

label: anterior region
Defs: Anatomical region anteriorly located on the body or body part.

label: digitate
Defs: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having distinct parts arising from a common point or center.

label: antero-ventral margin
Defs: Anatomical margin that is located on the antero-ventral region of the body or body part.

label: esophageal sphincter
Defs: A sphincter that is part of an esophagus.

label: propleuron
Defs: The region of the cuticle on the lateral region of the prothorax that is attached to the pronotum and the prosternum, and is attached to the procoxa by the procoxal muscle and the basal procoxal conjunctiva.

label: negative regulation of cellular amide metabolic process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving amides.

label: duodenum lamina propria
Defs: A lamina propria that is part of a duodenum.

label: positive regulation of transferase activity
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of transferase activity, the catalysis of the transfer of a group, e.g. a methyl group, glycosyl group, acyl group, phosphorus-containing, or other groups, from a donor compound to an acceptor.

label: non-striated muscle cell
Defs: Any muscle cell in which the fibers are not organised into sarcomeres.

label: muscle cell cellular homeostasis
Defs: The cellular homeostatic process that preserves a muscle cell in a stable functional or structural state.

label: venule of colon
Defs: A venule located in the colon.

label: gravid uterus
Defs: The uterus in pregnancy.

label: body of stomach
Defs: The body of stomach is the part of the stomach that lies between the fundus above and the pyloric antrum below; its boundaries are poorly defined[GO].

label: increased thickness
Defs: A thickness which is relatively high.

label: regulation of compound eye retinal cell programmed cell death
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of programmed cell death that occurs in the compound eye retina.

label: behavioural inactive
Defs: A behavioral quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s disposition to lack activity.

label: cell migration in hindbrain
Defs: The orderly movement of a cell that will reside in the hindbrain.

label: sinus venosus morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the sinus venosus is generated and organized. The sinus venosus is a heart chamber attached to the atrium on the venous side of the embryonic heart.

label: hindbrain
Defs: The most posterior of the three principal regions of the brain. In mammals and birds the hindbrain is divided into a rostral metencephalon and a caudal myelencephalon. In zebrafish, with the exception of the cerebellum, the ventral remainder of the metencephalon can be separated only arbitrarily from the more caudal myelencephalic portion of the medulla oblongata (From: Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain)[ZFA]. Organ component of neuraxis that has as its parts the pons, cerebellum and medulla oblongata[FMA].

label: hydroxylapatite
Defs: A phosphate mineral with the formula Ca5(PO4)3(OH).

label: cell chemotaxis
Defs: The directed movement of a motile cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient. Movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis).

label: regulation of microtubule polymerization
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of microtubule polymerization.

label: role
Defs: A role is particular behaviour which a material entity may exhibit.

label: antero-medial margin
Defs: Anatomical margin that is located on the antero-medial region of the body or body part.

label: T cell apoptotic process
Defs: Any apoptotic process in a T cell, a type of lymphocyte whose defining characteristic is the expression of a T cell receptor complex.

label: cellular chemical homeostasis
Defs: Any biological process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of a chemical at the level of the cell.

label: negative regulation of muscle hypertrophy
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of muscle hypertrophy.

label: alpha-amino-acid anion
Defs: An amino-acid anion obtained by deprotonation of any alpha-amino acid.

label: positive regulation of epidermis development
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of epidermis development.

label: cerebral artery
Defs: One of three main pairs of arteries and their branches, which irrigate the cerebrum of the brain.

label: regulation of translational termination
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of translational termination.

label: wet
Defs: A wetness quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being covered by a liquid.

label: positive regulation of transmembrane transport
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a solute from one side of a membrane to the other.

label: endothelial transcription factor GATA-2 (mouse)
Defs: An endothelial transcription factor GATA-2 that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: acetylcholine catabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of acetylcholine, the acetic acid ester of the organic base choline.

label: metathorcic discrimen
Defs: The discrimen of the metaventrite.

label: positive regulation of RNA metabolic process
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving RNA.

label: cloacal sphincter
Defs: A sphincter muscle that is part of a cloaca.

label: extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron
Defs: A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to structures not derived from telencephalon.

label: increased threshold
Defs: A threshold which is relatively high.

label: surface of cartilage
Defs: An anatomical surface that is part of a cartilage element.

label: regulation of pseudopodium assembly
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of pseudopodia.

label: epithelial cell development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an epithelial cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. An epithelial cell is a cell usually found in a two-dimensional sheet with a free surface.

label: cuticle of maxillary palpomere
Defs: The cuticle of the mere that is part of the maxillary palpus.

label: lens anterior epithelium
Defs: A layer of cuboidal epithelial cells bounded anteriorly by the capsule of the lens and posteriorly by the lens cortex.

label: yellow green
Defs: A color consisting of yellow and green hues.

label: regulation of cholangiocyte proliferation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cholangiocyte proliferation.

label: p-block molecular entity
Defs: A main group molecular entity that contains one or more atoms of a p-block element.

label: mesopleuro-mesocoxal conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva of the mesothorax that joins the mesopleuron and the mesocoxa.

label: decreased velocity
Defs: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s decreased rate of change of the position.

label: dendritic cell
Defs: A cell of hematopoietic origin, typically resident in particular tissues, specialized in the uptake, processing, and transport of antigens to lymph nodes for the purpose of stimulating an immune response via T cell activation. These cells are lineage negative (CD3-negative, CD19-negative, CD34-negative, and CD56-negative).

label: cloaca development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cloaca over time, from it\'s formation to the mature structure. The cloaca is the common chamber into which intestinal, genital and urinary canals open in vertebrates.

label: positive regulation of Schwann cell migration
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of Schwann cell migration.

label: multipotent
Defs: A cellular potency that is the capacity to form multiple differentiated cell types.

label: desaturated orange
Defs: A color consisting of orange hue and low saturation.

label: regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell migration
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the migration of the endothelial cells of blood vessels.

label: cellular component morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which cellular structures, including whole cells or cell parts, are generated and organized.

label: negative regulation of macrophage activation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of macrophage activation.

label: nonsynovial joint
Defs: Joint in which the articulating bones or cartilages are connected by ligaments or fibrocartilage without an intervening synovial cavity. Examples: sagittal suture, inferior tibiofibular syndesmosis, costochondral joint, pubic symphysis.

label: mesothoracic-metathoracic conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva of the insect thorax that connects the mesothorax and the metathorax.

label: protein localization to chromosome
Defs: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, a specific location on a chromosome.

label: hindbrain formation
Defs: The process that gives rise to the hindbrain. This process pertains to the initial formation of a structure from unspecified parts. The hindbrain is the region consisting of the medulla, pons and cerebellum. Areas of the hindbrain control motor and autonomic functions.

label: postgenal bridge
Defs: The region of the head capsule that is continuous with the postgena and adjacent to the foramen occipitale.

label: T-cell surface antigen CD2 (mouse)
Defs: A CD2 molecule that is encoded in the genome of mouse.

label: regulation of myeloid dendritic cell antigen processing and presentation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of myeloid dendritic cell antigen processing and presentation.

label: positive regulation of monocyte chemotaxis
Defs: Any process that increases the frequency, rate, or extent of monocyte chemotaxis.

label: cellular process
Defs: Any process that is carried out at the cellular level, but not necessarily restricted to a single cell. For example, cell communication occurs among more than one cell, but occurs at the cellular level.

label: anatomical entity
Defs: Biological entity that is either an individual member of a biological species or constitutes the structural organization of an individual member of a biological species.

label: elastic
Defs: An elasticity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s ability to recover its size and shape after deformation in any way.

label: glutamate biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glutamate, the anion of 2-aminopentanedioic acid.

label: mass unit
Defs: A unit which is a standard measure of the amount of matter/energy of a physical object.

label: median lingual swelling epithelium
Defs: An epithelium that is part of a median lingual swelling.

label: bulbous
Defs: A convex 3-D shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s resembling a teardrop.

label: chondroblast
Defs: Skeletogenic cell that is typically non-terminally differentiated, secretes an avascular, GAG rich matrix; is not buried in cartilage tissue matrix, retains the ability to divide, located adjacent to cartilage tissue (including within the perichondrium), and develops from prechondroblast (and thus prechondrogenic) cell.

label: irregularly shaped
Defs: A shape quality inhering on a bearer by virtue of a bearer\'s shape lacking in pattern or uniformity; for example, it may have sides of different lengths, different curvatures, or unequal angles.

label: smooth muscle cell of the brain vasculature
Defs: A vascular associated smooth muscle cell of the brain vasculature.

label: epithelium of left lung
Defs: An epithelium that is part of a left lung [Automatically generated definition].

label: regulation of catecholamine secretion
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of catecholamines.

label: negative regulation of motor neuron migration
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of motor neuron migration.

label: regulation of Golgi to plasma membrane protein transport
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the transport of proteins from the Golgi to the plasma membrane.

label: right side of
Defs: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being located on right side of a another entity.

label: regulation of defense response to bacterium
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of defense response to bacterium.

label: glial cell development
Defs: The process aimed at the progression of a glial cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell.

label: cranio-antennal articulation
Defs: The articulation between the scapus and the cranium.

label: normal avidity
Defs: An avidity which is relatively normal or average.

label: DNA-binding transcription factor binding
Defs: Binding to a DNA-binding transcription factor, a protein that interacts with a specific DNA sequence (sometimes referred to as a motif) within the regulatory region of a gene to modulate transcription.

label: negative regulation of hematopoietic stem cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of hematopoietic stem cell proliferation.

label: reticular formation
Defs: A composite substructure of the brainstem that consists of the midbrain reticular formation, the pontine reticular formation and the medullary reticular formation ( Carpenter-1983 ).

label: tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase type 5
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human ACP5 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: blood vessel maturation
Defs: A developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for a blood vessel to attain its fully functional state.

label: radial symmetry
Defs: A symmetry quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having equal proportion around a central point or axis.

label: ciliated cell of the bronchus
Defs: A ciliated cell of the bronchus.

label: pronoto-phragmal muscle
Defs: The dorsal longitudinal thoracic muscle that is attached to the pronotum and the prophragma.

label: hydrides
Defs: Hydrides are chemical compounds of hydrogen with other chemical elements.

label: trachea development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a trachea over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The trachea is the portion of the airway that attaches to the bronchi as it branches.

label: mislocalised dorsally
Defs: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being positioned towards the back or upper surface of an organism.

label: positive regulation of plasma membrane bounded cell projection assembly
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of plasma membrane bounded cell projection assembly.

label: punctiform
Defs: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being small and resembling a point.

label: source code module
Defs: A source code module is a directive information entity that specifies, using a programming language, some algorithm.

label: vesicle
Defs: Any small, fluid-filled, spherical organelle enclosed by membrane.

label: prominence
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the degree to which the bearers stands out or projects beyond a surface or line.

label: lung secretory cell differentiation
Defs: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a lung secretory cell. A lung secretory cell is a specialized epithelial cell of the lung that contains large secretory granules in its apical part.

label: multiporous plate
Defs: The multiporous sensillum that is flat.

label: regulation of respiratory gaseous exchange
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the process of gaseous exchange between an organism and its environment.

label: brachiocephalic vein
Defs: The left and right brachiocephalic veins in the upper chest are formed by the union of each corresponding internal jugular vein and subclavian vein. This is at the level of the sternoclavicular joint. These great vessels merge to form the superior vena cava. The brachiocephalic veins are the major veins returning blood to the superior vena cava.

label: compound organ
Defs: Anatomical structure that has as its parts two or more multi-tissue structures of at least two different types and which through specific morphogenetic processes forms a single distinct structural unit demarcated by bona fide boundaries from other distinct anatomical structures of different types.

label: cranio-labral muscle
Defs: The somatic muscle that is attached to the head capsule and the labrum.

label: cellular response to serotonin
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a serotonin stimulus.

label: chordate embryonic development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the embryo over time, from zygote formation through a stage including a notochord and neural tube until birth or egg hatching.

label: positive regulation of response to stimulus
Defs: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of a response to a stimulus. Response to stimulus is a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus.

label: cellular adhesivity
Defs: A cellular quality that exists by virtue of the disposition of the cell to adhere to other cells and molecules, through the emergent action of the molecular parts of the cell surface.

label: pancreas secretion
Defs: A secretion that is part of a pancreas [Automatically generated definition].

label: recent
Defs: A quality of a process which occurs near to or not long before the present.

label: negative regulation of cardiac myofibril assembly
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac myofibril assembly.

label: cranial nerve nucleus
Defs: Nucleus that receives projections from or contains neurons that send projections through one of the cranial nerves.

label: negative regulation of synaptic transmission, glutamatergic
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of glutamatergic synaptic transmission, the process of communication from a neuron to another neuron across a synapse using the neurotransmitter glutamate.

label: regulation of nucleobase-containing compound transport
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: regulation of excitatory synapse assembly
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of excitatory synapse assembly.

label: serotonin catabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine), a monoamine neurotransmitter occurring in the peripheral and central nervous systems, also having hormonal properties.

label: negative regulation of cellular amino acid biosynthetic process
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cellular amino acid biosynthetic process.

label: epithelium
Defs: Portion of tissue, that consists of one or more layers of epithelial cells connected to each other by cell junctions and which is underlain by a basal lamina. Examples: simple squamous epithelium, glandular cuboidal epithelium, transitional epithelium, myoepithelium[CARO].

label: epitope
Defs: The biological role played by a material entity when bound by a receptor of the adaptive immune system. Specific site on an antigen to which an antibody binds.

label: interneuron
Defs: Most generally any neuron which is not motor or sensory. Interneurons may also refer to neurons whose axons remain within a particular brain region as contrasted with projection neurons which have axons projecting to other brain regions.

label: regulation of cellular amine catabolic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways leading to the breakdown of amines.

label: smooth muscle of esophagus
Defs: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a esophagus [Automatically generated definition].

label: regulation of embryonic camera-type eye development
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of embryonic camera-type eye development.

label: arrow-shaped
Defs: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s forming two equal obtuse triangles with a short side in common.

label: protein localization to postsynapse
Defs: Any process in which a protein is transported to, and/or maintained at the postsynapse, the part of a synapse that is part of the post-synaptic cell.

label: endocardium morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structure of the endocardium is generated and organized. The endocardium is an anatomical structure comprised of an endothelium and an extracellular matrix that forms the innermost layer of tissue of the heart, and lines the heart chambers.

label: hyaluronic acid binding
Defs: Binding to hyaluronic acid, a polymer composed of repeating dimeric units of glucuronic acid and N-acetyl glucosamine.

label: white matter of midbrain
Defs: A white matter that is part of the midbrain.

label: cholinergic synapse
Defs: A synapse that uses acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter.

label: establishment or maintenance of cytoskeleton polarity
Defs: Any cellular process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of polarized cytoskeletal structures.

label: corneal endothelium
Defs: A monolayer of specialized, flattened, mitochondria-rich cells that lines the posterior surface of the cornea and faces the anterior chamber of the eye[WP].

label: associating information with a centrally registered identifier in its registry
Defs: A planned process in which a CRID registry associates an information content entity with a CRID symbol

label: lateral structure
Defs: Any structure that is placed on one side of the left-right axis of a bilaterian.

label: pyramidal neuron development
Defs: The progression of a pyramidal neuron from its initial formation to its mature state.

label: obsolete2_digital document
Defs: A digital document is a digital entity consisting of an electronic file which can be rendered into human-readable form by one or more computational applications.  The digital document does not refer to the information content of the document but to an instance of the file.

label: normal turgor
Defs: A turgor which is relatively normal or average

label: coelomic fluid
Defs: A bodily fluid that is located in the coelom.

label: sphincter of hepatopancreatic ampulla
Defs: Muscular valve that controls the flow of digestive juices (bile and pancreatic juice) through the ampulla of Vater into the second part of the duodenum. Relaxed by the hormone Cholecystokinin (CCK) via vasoactive intestinal polypeptide (VIP).[WP].

label: mucosa of larynx
Defs: The mucous lining of the larynx, which is composed of squamous epithelium in the upper larynx and ciliated columnar epithelium in the lower larynx.

label: positive regulation of dopamine biosynthetic process
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of dopamine biosynthetic process.

label: positive regulation of cardiac muscle hypertrophy
Defs: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of the enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of the heart due to an increase in size (not length) of individual cardiac muscle fibers, without cell division.

label: biological_process
Defs: A biological process represents a specific objective that the organism is genetically programmed to achieve. Biological processes are often described by their outcome or ending state, e.g., the biological process of cell division results in the creation of two daughter cells (a divided cell) from a single parent cell. A biological process is accomplished by a particular set of molecular functions carried out by specific gene products (or macromolecular complexes), often in a highly regulated manner and in a particular temporal sequence.

label: regulation of actin cytoskeleton organization by cell-cell adhesion
Defs: Any cell-cell adhesion process that modulates the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising actin filaments and their associated proteins.

label: dark phase
Defs: A phase which occurs during dark cycle.

label: secretory granule
Defs: A small subcellular vesicle, surrounded by a membrane, that is formed from the Golgi apparatus and contains a highly concentrated protein destined for secretion. Secretory granules move towards the periphery of the cell and upon stimulation, their membranes fuse with the cell membrane, and their protein load is exteriorized. Processing of the contained protein may take place in secretory granules.

label: positive regulation of T cell migration
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of T cell migration.

label: iron import into cell
Defs: The directed movement of iron ions from outside of a cell into the cytoplasmic compartment. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

label: negative regulation of epithelial cell proliferation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of epithelial cell proliferation.

label: regulation of chondrocyte development
Defs: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the process whose specific outcome is the progression of a chondrocyte over time, from its commitment to its mature state. Chondrocyte development does not include the steps involved in committing a chondroblast to a chondrocyte fate.

label: basal cell
Defs: Undifferentiated; mitotic stem cell for other epithelial cell types; rounded or elliptical with little cytoplasm and few organelles; contain cytokeratin intermediate filament.

label: cyclic organic group
Defs: An organic group that consists of a closed ring. It may be a substituent or a skeleton.

label: intertarsomeral conjunctiva
Defs: The conjunctiva is encircled by a tarsomere that encircles another tarsomere.

label: positive regulation of adaptive immune response based on somatic recombination of immune receptors built from immunoglobulin superfamily domains
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of an adaptive immune response based on somatic recombination of immune receptors built from immunoglobulin superfamily domains. An example of this process is found in the Gnathostomata.

label: cell development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a specific fate.

label: diandrous
Defs: A phenotypic sex quality inhering in a  plant organism or a population of plants in which the flowers have two stamens.

label: lymphoid progenitor cell differentiation
Defs: The process in which a precursor cell type acquires the specialized features of a lymphoid progenitor cell. Lymphoid progenitor cells include progenitor cells for any of the lymphoid lineages.

label: lung mesenchyme
Defs: The mass of tissue made up of mesenchymal cells in the lung.

label: neuron differentiation
Defs: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a neuron.

label: vagus nerve maturation
Defs: A developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for the vagus nerve to attain its fully functional state. This nerve is primarily sensory but also has visceromotor components. It originates in the brain stem and controls many autonomic functions of the heart, lungs, stomach, pharynx, larynx, trachea, esophagus and other gastrointestinal tract components. It controls some motor functions such as speech. The sensory branches mediate sensation from the pharynx, larynx, thorax and abdomen; it also innervates taste buds in the epiglottis.

label: notochordal plate
Defs: The notochordal plate is the dorsal part of the notochordal process when the ventral portion breaks down. It is continuous laterally with the endoderm that composes the roof of the primitive foregut and is in contact dorsally with the neural tube. The folding off of the notochordal plate gives rise to the notochord.

label: submucosa of stomach
Defs: The fibrous connective tissue layer beneath the stomach mucosa.

label: positive regulation of skeletal muscle tissue growth
Defs: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of skeletal muscle growth.

label: figures section
Defs: A part of a document that contains one or more figures.

label: steroid acid
Defs: Any steroid substituted by at least one carboxy group.

label: low affinity immunoglobulin gamma Fc region receptor II
Defs: An immunoglobulin gamma Fc receptor II/III/IV that is a translation product of the mouse Fcgr2 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: negative regulation of peptide hormone secretion
Defs: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of the regulated release of a peptide hormone from secretory granules.

label: AV node cell action potential
Defs: An action potential that occurs in an atrioventricular node cardiac muscle cell.

label: negative regulation of cell migration
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration.

label: collagen trimer
Defs: A protein complex consisting of three collagen chains assembled into a left-handed triple helix. These trimers typically assemble into higher order structures.

label: female gonad morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which a female gonad is generated and organized.

label: invariant shape
Defs: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s lacking or not exhibiting variation of shape.

label: excitatory postsynaptic potential
Defs: A process that leads to a temporary increase in postsynaptic potential due to the flow of positively charged ions into the postsynaptic cell. The flow of ions that causes an EPSP is an excitatory postsynaptic current (EPSC) and makes it easier for the neuron to fire an action potential.

label: glycan
Defs: Any oligosaccharide, polysaccharide or their derivatives consisting of monosaccharides or monosaccharide derivatives linked by glycosidic bonds. See also http://www.ontobee.org/ontology/GNO?iri=http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GNO_00000001.

label: white matter of forebrain
Defs: A white matter that is part of the forebrain.

label: acetate metabolic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways involving acetate, the anion of acetic acid.

label: positive regulation of myeloid leukocyte cytokine production involved in immune response
Defs: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the production of a cytokine that contributes to the immune response.

label: positive regulation of tissue remodeling
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of tissue remodeling.

label: regulation of iron ion transport
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of iron ions (Fe) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: superior olivary nucleus morphogenesis
Defs: The process in which the anatomical structure of the superior olivary nucleus is generated and organized. In mice, the superior olivary nucleus is a small cylindrical mass on the dorsal surface of the lateral part of the trapezoid body of the pons, and it is situated immediately above the inferior olivary nucleus. It receives projections from the cochlear nucleus and thus is involved in the perception of sound.

label: irradiated
Defs: A quality of a substance inhering in a bearer by virtue of it being currently or previously exposed to electromagnetic radiation,

label: bodily fluid
Defs: Liquid components of living organisms. includes fluids that are excreted or secreted from the body as well as body water that normally is not.

label: regulation of hematopoietic stem cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of hematopoietic stem cell differentiation.

label: positive regulation of cardiac chamber morphogenesis
Defs: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac chamber morphogenesis.

label: alternation
Defs: A quality of a single process inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s successive change from one thing or state to another and back again.

label: tripodal
Defs: A 3-D shape with three supports or legs.

label: optic cup
Defs: Multi-tissue structure that is comprised of neural and non-neural epithelial layers which will form the retina and retinal pigmented epithelium of the mature eye[ZFA]. double walled structured formed by expansion and invagination of the distal end of the optic vesicle that develops into the pigmented and sensory layers of the retina while the mouth of the optic cup eventually forms the pupil of the eye[MP].

label: decreased photosensitivity
Defs: A photosensitivity which is relatively low.

label: early embryonic cell (metazoa)
Defs: A cell found in the embryo before the formation of all the gem layers is complete.

label: RNA transport
Defs: The directed movement of RNA, ribonucleic acids, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: eye mesenchyme
Defs: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing camera-type eye.

label: neurotransmitter biosynthetic process
Defs: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of any of a group of substances that are released on excitation from the axon terminal of a presynaptic neuron of the central or peripheral nervous system and travel across the synaptic cleft to either excite or inhibit the target cell.

label: hepatic duct development
Defs: The progression of the hepatic duct over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The hepatic duct is the duct that leads from the liver to the common bile duct.

label: branched
Defs: A branchiness quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s having branches.

label: intramuscular adipose tissue
Defs: Adipose tissue which is located throughout skeletal muscle and is responsible for the marbling seen in certain cuts of beef. In humans, excess accumulation of intramuscular fat is associated with insulin resistance and type 2 diabetes.

label: pelvic appendage apical ectodermal ridge
Defs: An apical ectodermal ridge that is part of a pelvic appendage bud.

label: moderately well differentiated
Defs: A cellular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of its lacking few of the cellular characteristics which would allow it to be fully differentiated.

label: epipleurite
Defs: The sclerite of the insect thorax that is surrounded by the noto-pleural conjunctiva and is adjacent to the wing.

label: negative regulation of protein localization to presynapse
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to presynapse.

label: T-cell surface glycoprotein CD5
Defs: A protein that is a translation product of the human CD5 gene or a 1:1 ortholog thereof.

label: cuboidal oviduct epithelium
Defs: A cuboidal epithelium that is part of a oviduct.

label: cortical interneuron
Defs: An interneuron that has its soma located in the cerebral cortex.

label: cellular monovalent inorganic cation homeostasis
Defs: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of monovalent inorganic cations at the level of a cell.

label: phosphate ion binding
Defs: Binding to a phosphate ion.

label: mesentery of small intestine
Defs: The peritoneum responsible for connecting the jejunum and ileum (parts of the small intestine) to the back wall of the abdomen. Between the two sheets of peritoneum are blood vessels, lymph vessels, and nerves. This allows these parts of the small intestine to move relatively freely within the abdominopelvic cavity. The brain, however, cannot map sensation accurately, so sensation is usually referred to the midline, an example of referred pain[WP].

label: coxal muscle
Defs: The somatic muscle that inserts in the coxa.

label: regulation of lymphocyte apoptotic process
Defs: Any process that modulates the occurrence or rate of lymphocyte death by apoptotic process.

label: ribosome biogenesis
Defs: A cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of ribosome subunits; includes transport to the sites of protein synthesis.

label: corneal epithelial cell migration
Defs: The orderly movement of a corneal  epithelial cell from one site to another, often during the development of a multicellular organism.

label: lipid binding
Defs: Binding to a lipid.

label: tendon collagen fibril
Defs: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of tendon tissue that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity.

label: cell-cell junction
Defs: A cell junction that forms a connection between two or more cells of an organism; excludes direct cytoplasmic intercellular bridges, such as ring canals in insects.

label: signaling receptor binding
Defs: Binding to one or more specific sites on a receptor molecule, a macromolecule that undergoes combination with a hormone, neurotransmitter, drug or intracellular messenger to initiate a change in cell function.

label: RNA localization to chromatin
Defs: A process in which RNA is transported to and maintained in a part of a chromosome that is organized into chromatin.

label: embryonic blood vessel endothelial progenitor cell
Defs: An endothelial progenitor cell that participates in angiogenesis during development.

label: cell motility involved in cerebral cortex radial glia guided migration
Defs: The movement of a cell along the process of a radial glial cell involved in cerebral cortex glial-mediated radial migration.

label: airway submucosal gland
Defs: A submucosal gland found in a respiratory tract.

label: replacement element
Defs: Skeletal element that forms as a replacement or substitution of another element or tissue.

label: embryonic cloaca
Defs: Endoderm-lined chamber that develops as pouch-like dilation of the caudal end of the hindgut and receives the allantois ventrally and two mesonephric ducts laterally; caudally it ends blindly at the cloacal membrane formed by the union of proctodeal (anal pit) ectoderm and cloacal endoderm, with no intervening mesoderm[MP].

label: decreased pigmentation
Defs: A degree of pigmentation quality that is relative low.

label: presternum
Defs: The part of the sternum that is attached to the anterior margin of the basisternum.

label: response to organonitrogen compound
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an organonitrogen stimulus. An organonitrogen compound is formally a compound containing at least one carbon-nitrogen bond.

label: locomotion
Defs: Self-propelled movement of a cell or organism from one location to another.

label: concealed by
Defs: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being hidden from view or covered by another entity.

label: sympathetic nervous system development
Defs: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the sympathetic nervous system over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The sympathetic nervous system is one of the two divisions of the vertebrate autonomic nervous system (the other being the parasympathetic nervous system). The sympathetic preganglionic neurons have their cell bodies in the thoracic and lumbar regions of the spinal cord and connect to the paravertebral chain of sympathetic ganglia. Innervate heart and blood vessels, sweat glands, viscera and the adrenal medulla. Most sympathetic neurons, but not all, use noradrenaline as a post-ganglionic neurotransmitter.

label: pelvic region of trunk
Defs: The lower segment of the trunk, inferioposterior to the abdomen proper, in the transition area between the trunk and the lower limbs.

label: splayed
Defs: A curvature quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer\'s being curved outward.

label: cellular response to salt
Defs: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a salt stimulus.

label: cellular developmental process
Defs: A biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of a cell over time from an initial condition to a later condition.

label: venous system smooth muscle
Defs: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a venous system [Automatically generated definition].

label: sutured to
Defs: Structural quality inhering in a bearer in which a joint has apposed bony surfaces united by fibrous tissue, permitting no movement; found only between bones.

label: placenta
Defs: Organ of metabolic interchange between fetus and mother, partly of embryonic origin and partly of maternal origin[GO]. The fetal portion of the placenta is known as the villous chorion. The maternal portion is known as the decidua basalis. The two portions are held together by anchoring villi that are anchored to the decidua basalis by the cytotrophoblastic shell.

label: secretory vesicle
Defs: A cytoplasmic, membrane bound vesicle that is capable of fusing to the plasma membrane to release its contents into the extracellular space.

label: multi fate stem cell
Defs: A stem cell that can give rise to multiple lineages of cells.

label: nitrogen compound transport
Defs: The directed movement of nitrogen-containing compounds into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: negative regulation of stem cell differentiation
Defs: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of stem cell differentiation.

label: nucleus disassembly
Defs: The disaggregation of a nucleus into its constituent components.

label: optic vesicle morphogenesis
Defs: The developmental process pertaining to the formation and shaping of the optic vesicle. This process begins with the specific processes that contribute to the appearance of the vesicle and ends when the vesicle has evaginated.
